      <!-- <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p> -->
      <!-- </paragraphs> -->


      <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIntegralSecant">
        <title>The Integral of the Secant</title>
        <p>
          As we<rsq/>ve just seen
          once integration by substitution has been mastered finding the
          integral of <m>\tan (x)</m> is straightforward. Based on this
          experience it would seem reasonable to assume that 
          <m>\int \sec (x)\dx{x}</m> would be equally straightforward. 
        </p>
        <p>
          And it is, sort of. We just need to make the right substitution
          but what that could be is far from obvious.
        </p>
        <p>
          We<rsq/>ll use the substitution <m>u=\tan (x) +\sec(x) </m>. You
          almost certainly don<rsq/>e see how this will work, but that is
          part of the point we want to make with this example. You are
          free to make any substitution you like, and sometimes the right
          substitution is not obvious. The only way to find out if a given
          substitution will work is to try it and see. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Observe that if

          <me>
            u=\tan(x)+\sec(x)
          </me>
          then
          <md>
            <mrow>        \dx{u}\amp{}= \left( \sec^2(x) +
            \sec(x)\tan(x)\right){} \dx{x}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\sec(x)\underbrace{\left(\sec(x)+\tan(x) \right)}_{=u} \dx{x} </mrow>
          </md>
          and so 
          <me>\sec (x)\dx{x} = \frac{\dx{u}}{u}.</me>
          Thus
          <me>
            \int\sec (x)\dx{x} =\int \frac{\dx{u}}{u}
            =\ln\abs{u} +C =
            \ln\abs{\sec (x) + \tan (x)} +C
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          This integration is sometimes taught using the following
          <q>trick</q> which is equivalent to our development above:

          <md>
            <mrow>\int\sec(x)\dx{x} \amp{}= \int\sec(x)\underbrace{\frac{\tan (x)+\sec (x)}{\tan
            (x)+\sec (x)}}_{=1}\dx{x}.
            </mrow>
            <intertext>Now let <m>u=\tan(x)+\sec(x) </m> so that <m>\dx{u}
            =\sec(x)\tan(x)+\sec^2(x) </m> so that</intertext>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\int\frac1u\dx{u}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\ln\abs{u}+C</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\ln\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)} +C</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          As an means of computing the integral this trick is acceptable. 
          But as a teaching example it leaves a lot to be desired.<!--  In -->
          <!--   particular, there is no discernible reason for the substition -->
          <!--   <m>u=\sec (x)+\tan(x) </m> (equivalently, multiplying by <m>1</m> in -->
          <!--   the form <m>\frac{\sec (x)+\tan(x)}{\sec (x)+\tan(x)}</m>). -->
          <!--   These are both  clearly tricks that were devised after the value of the -->
          <!--   integral had  been determined in some fashion. -->
          <!-- </p> -->
          <!-- <p> -->
          Clearly whoever first computed the value of this integral found it by
          some other means (possibly by guessing) and then realized that
          <!-- multiplying by <m>\frac{\tan (x)+\sec (x)}{\tan(x)+\sec (x)}</m> and -->
          using the substitution <m>u=\tan(x)+\sec(x) </m> would suffice, even
          if it is not very illuminative.
        </p>
      </example>
      <paragraphs xml:id="DIGRESSIONIntPolySecTan">
        <title>DIGRESSION:  The Integral of an Arbitrary Polynomial
        in
        <m>\sec(x) </m> and <m>\tan{x} </m></title>

        
        <p>
          This digression is based on the paper
          <pubtitle>
            <url href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589620"
                 visual="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589620">Integrating
            Polynomials in Secant and Tangent</url> </pubtitle>, by
            Jonathan P. McCammond, The American Mathematical Monthly,
            Nov., 1999, Vol. 106, No. 9
        </p>

        <aside>
          <title>Comment</title>
          <p>
            There is an old joke that a technique is a trick that
            you use more than once.
          </p>
        </aside>
        <p>
          We have called the substitution <m>u=\tan(x)+\sec(x) </m> a
          trick but what seems to be a trick is often a special case of
          more general technique. Th is the situation here.
          We would like to find the underlying structure behind <xref ref="EXAMPLEIntegralSecant"></xref>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The technique follows from definitions 

          <mdn>
            <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubA">u\amp{}=\sec(x)+\tan(x)</mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubB">v\amp{}=\sec(x)-\tan(x)</mrow>
          </mdn>

          from which we see that

          <mdn>
            <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA">\sec(x) \amp{}=\frac12 (u+v)</mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubB">\tan(x) \amp{}=\frac12 (u-v).</mrow>
          </mdn>
        </p>
        <problem>
          <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Show that <men xml:id="EQUATIONSecTanEq1">uv=1</men>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Show that <men xml:id="EQUATIONSetTanDifferentials">\sec(x)\dx{x} = \frac1u \dx{u} = - \frac1v \dx{v}. </men>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>

        </problem>

        <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIntPolySecTan">
          <task xml:id="PROBLEMIntPolySecTanA">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For our first example we will compute 
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x} \amp{}= \int \sec^2(x)\sec{x}\dx{x} 
                  </mrow>
                </md>
                From <xref ref="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA">equation</xref> we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x}\amp{}=\frac14\int(u+v)^2\sec(x)\dx{x}
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp{}=\frac14\int(u^2+2uv+v^2)\sec(x)\dx{x}
                  </mrow>
                </md>
                and from <xref ref="EQUATIONSecTanEq1">equation</xref> we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x}=\amp{}\frac14\int(u^2+2+v^2))\sec(x)\dx{x}
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    =\amp{}\frac14\int
                    u^2\left(\frac{1}{u}\dx{u}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\int\sec(x)\dx{x} -\frac14
                    \int v^2\left(\frac{1}{v}\dx{v}\right)
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    =\amp{}\frac18\left(u^2-v^2\right)+\frac12\int\sec(x)\dx{x}
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    =\amp{}\frac18\left[\left(\sec(x)+\tan(x)\right)^2-\left(
                    \sec(x)-\tan(x)\right)^2  \right] 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp{}+\frac12\ln{\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)}}+C
                  </mrow>
                </md>
                So finally,
                <men xml:id="EQUATIONAverageIntegral">
                  \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x}=\frac12\left(\sec(x)\tan(x)+\ln{\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)}}\right)+C.
                </men>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <conclusion>
            <p>
              Do you notice anything interesting about <xref
              ref="EQUATIONAverageIntegral">equation</xref>? Look
              closely. It says that the integral of <m>\sec^3(x) </m> is
              the average of the derivative of <m>\sec(x) </m> and the
              integral of <m>\sec(x) </m>. 
            </p>

            <p>
              As far as we know this is not an extremely useful fact, but
              it is interesting. Prof. Rick Poss of Norbert College found
              noticed this fact and found it sufficiently interesting that
              he and his colleague John Frohliger decided to determine if there were
              other functions with this property. The results of their
              investigations were  published in 
              <pubtitle>
                Mathematics Magazine, Vol. 62, #4, October 1989
                </pubtitle> with the title 

                <url href="https://www-jstor-org.ezaccess.libraries.psu.edu/stable/2689766?seq=1" visual="https://www-jstor-org.ezaccess.libraries.psu.edu">Just
                an Average Integral</url>

            </p>

          </conclusion>



        </example>
        <p>
          In fact, in the paper cited above, McCammond shows that if
          <m>P(s,t)</m> is any polynomial in two variables then

          <me>\int P\left(\sec(x), \tan(x)\right)\dx{x}</me>

          can be evaluated using the substitutions in equations <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubA"></xref>,        <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubB"></xref>, <xref
          ref="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA"></xref>, <xref
          ref="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubB"></xref>,  <xref
          ref="EQUATIONSecTanEq1"></xref>, <xref
          ref="EQUATIONSetTanDifferentials"></xref>,
          <!--  and <xref -->
          <!-- ref="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubB"></xref>, their properties in equations -->
          <!-- <xref ref="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA"></xref> and <xref ref=", -->
          <!-- EQUATIONSecTanInvSubB"></xref> above, --> 
          and the judicious use of the
          Pythagorean trigonometric identity 
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONPythSecTan">\tan^2(x)+1=\sec^2(x).</men>
        </p>

        <exercise  xml:id="PROBLEMPolySecTan">


          <introduction>
            <p>


              Evaluate the integrals and differentiate your  solution to confirm
              that it is  correct.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle
                \int \sec^5(x) \dx{x} = \frac{1}{16}\sec^3(x)
                +\sec{x} \tan(x) +3\ln 
                \left(
                \sec(x) +\tan (x)
                \right) +C</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int \tan^4(x) \dx{x} = \frac{1}{12}\sec^2(x) \tan(x)
                +\frac{1}{24}\tan^3(x) - \frac14\tan(x) +C</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int \sec^4(x)\tan(x) \dx{x}
                  = 
                  <!--   \left[ -->
                  \frac{1}{16}\sec^3(x)\amp{} \tan(x) +\frac{1}{16}\sec(x) \tan^3(x)
                  <!-- \left] -->
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    +\amp{}\frac{1}{128} \left( \sec(x) - \tan(x)
                    \right) 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp{}+\frac{1}{96} \left(\sec(x) + \tan(x)\right) + C
                    <!--   \right]+C -->
                  </mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \sec^3(x)\tan^5(x) \dx{x} </m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
        </exercise>
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   These substitutions are clever and they give us an elegant solution -->
        <!--   but we do not necessarily want an elegant solution. In most cases -->
        <!--   where the evaluation of an integral is required we<rsq/>ll just want -->
        <!--   obtain a -->
        <!--   solution in the most efficient manner possible. -->
        <!-- </p> -->

        <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPolySecTanByTrigSub">

          <introduction>
            <p>
              Evaluate the following integrals and differentiate your  solution to confirm
              that it is  correct. The method we<rsq/>ve described in this
              digression will work, but is not the necessarily always the most efficient
              method available.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \sec^2(x)+\sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x} </m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \sec^3(x)\tan(x)+\tan^3(x)\sec(x)\dx{x} </m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \left(1+\sec(x)+\sec^2(x)+\sec^3(x)+\sec^4(x) \right)\tan(x)
                \dx{{x}  }</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \left(1+\tan(x)+\tan^2(x)+\tan^3(x)+\tan^4(x) \right)\sec(x)
                \dx{{x}  }</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>

        </exercise>


        <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPolyCscCot">

          <introduction>
            <p>
              Evaluate the following integrals and differentiate your  solution to confirm
              that it is  correct. The method we<rsq/>ve described in this
              digression will work, but is not the necessarily always the most efficient
              method available.
              (You will need to find substitutions analogous to those we developed
              above.)
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \csc^2(x)+\csc(x)\cot(x)\dx{x} </m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \csc^3(x)\cot(x)+\cot^3(x)\csc(x)\dx{x} </m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \left(1+\csc(x)+\csc^2(x)+\csc^3(x)+\csc^4(x) \right)\cot(x)
                \dx{{x}  }</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int \left(1+\cot(x)+\cot^2(x)+\cot^3(x)+\cot^4(x) \right)\csc(x)
                \dx{{x}  }</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>

        </exercise>


        <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
      </paragraphs>

      <exercises>
        <title> Exercises and Drills: Integration by Substitution</title>



        <exercisegroup  cols="2">
          <title>Drills</title>


          <introduction>
            <p>
              Use an appropriate substitution to compute each of these
              integrals. Use the formulas in both <xref
              ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> and <xref
              ref="FIGURECRC"></xref> as needed.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <exercise>


            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int 2x \left(x^2+1\right)^3\dx{x}</m>

              </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
              <p>
                This problem can be done by simply expanding the integrand
                algebraically. That will work but do you really want to do
                that?
              </p>
            </hint>

          </exercise>
          <exercise>


            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int 2x\left(x^2+1\right)^{150}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
