    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONHangingChainSolDeriv">
      <title>Deriving the Solution of the Hanging Chain Problem</title>

      <p>
        We have seen (in <xref ref="EXAMPLEHardDiffeq"></xref>) that in
        order to derive the  formula for the catenary curve we need to
        determine  <m>z(x)</m> from <xref
        ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt2">equation</xref> which  requires
        that we compute the  integral

        <me> \int{\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z} } </me>.

        It is not at all obvious but the substitution we need is
        <m>z=\tan{\theta } </m>.     We will
        discuss how we came up with this particular substitution in the
        <xref ref="SUBSECTIONTrigSubst" text="custom">next section</xref>.
        For now we simply observe that this substitution 
        has a slightly different character than the substitutions we made
        in <xref ref="SUBSECTIONSimpleSubstitution"></xref>.  
      </p>
      <p>
        Previously, we would have set the substitution variable (usually
        <m>u</m>) to be some complex expression in the integration
        variable (usually <m>x</m>) in order to make the integrand
        simpler, or <q>easier on the eyes.</q> For example, given <m>\int
        \cos(2x){\dx{x}}</m> we<rsq/>d let <m>u=2x</m> to obtain the
        simpler integral
        <m>\frac12\int \cos(u)\dx{u} </m> which we can compute via entry
        #7 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>.
      </p>
      <p>
        But 

        notice that if we make the substitution <m>z=\tan(\theta)</m> then

        <m>\dx{\theta{}}=\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> so the integral
        does not get simpler, it gets  more complicated:
        <men  xml:id="EQUATIONInvSubst1"> 
          \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}= \int\frac{\sec^2(\theta )}
          {\sqrt{1+\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}
          </men>.
          For that reason this form of substitution is sometimes called
          <term>Inverse Substitution</term>.
      </p>

      <p>
        In addition to the substitution <m>z=\tan \left(\theta \right)</m>,
        we  add the
        condition: 
        <me>
          -\frac{\pi }{2}\lt\theta \lt\frac{\pi }{2} 
          </me>.  
          You will see why we added this restriction in a moment. For now
          notice that for <m>\theta </m> in this range, we still allow for
          <m>-\infty \lt z\lt\infty </m>, so <m>z</m> can still be any real
          number.
      </p>

      <p>
        Clearly <xref ref="EQUATIONInvSubst1">equation</xref> is
        considerably more complicated than the original
        problem. (In this situation a former teacher of one of the authors was fond
        of joking <q>Why simplify when you can complicate?</q>)
      </p>
      <p>

        But remember that our goal is not to make the integral simpler,
        our goal is to make the integral doable. In this case  the trigonometric identity
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONPythTrigSecTan">\sec^2( \theta ) = 1+\tan^2
        (\theta )</men> 
        will be very helpful.
      </p>

      <p>
        Thus we see 
        that <me>\sqrt{1+\tan^2(\theta )}=\sqrt{\sec^2( \theta )}=\abs{\sec(
        \theta )}</me> because 
        as we observed  in  <xref
        ref="DIGRESSIONAbsValSqrt" text="custom">DIGRESSION: The Absolute
        Value Function</xref> <m>\sqrt{x^2}=\abs{x}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is one of several ways that the Absolute Value can slip into
        our computations. This is annoying, but it is also
        unavoidable. The square root of <m>x^2</m> is not
        <m>x</m> no matter how much we<rsq/>d like it to be, and that fact
        has to be dealt with.
      </p>
      <p>
        However when we are simply trying to find an antiderivative we can
        usually ignore the Absolute Value. Because this is true and because
        dealing with the details of the Absolute Value function is a
        complication we don<rsq/>t need right now we will usually impose
        conditions on the problem that prevent its appearance as we did
        above.  Notice that the condition <m>\frac{-\pi }{2}\lt x \lt
        \frac{\pi }{2}</m> did not arise from the problem. We simply imposed
        it for our own convenience.
      </p>
      <p>
        That constraint on the values <m>\theta</m> guarantees that <m>\sec
        \left(\theta \right)\gt 0</m> so that <m>\abs{\sec (\theta )}=\sec(
        \theta )</m>.

        From this identity and <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPythTrigSecTan">equation</xref> we see that

        <md>
          <mrow>
            \int\frac{1} {\sqrt{1+z^2}} \dx{z}
            \amp{}=\int\frac{\sec^2(\theta)}{\abs{\sec(\theta)}}\ \dx{\theta}
            <!-- </mrow> -->
            <!-- <mrow> -->
            <!--   \amp{} -->=\int\frac{\sec^2(\theta )}{{\sec \left(\theta \right)\
            }}\dx{\theta}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp{}=\int\sec (\theta )\dx{\theta} =\ln
            \abs{\tan \left(\theta \right) +\sec \left(\theta
            \right)}+C
          </mrow>
        </md>

      </p>
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   We will discuss this -->
      <!--   further when we have finished with this problem but notice that -->
      <!--   another  -->
      <!--   absolute value has popped up   in the logarithm.  -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   We<rsq/>ll put things -->
      <!--   back in terms of <m>z</m>.  so that <men -->
      <!--   xml:id="EQUATIONSecInt">\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z} -->
      <!--   =\ln\abs{\tan(\theta)+\sec(\theta)}+c </men>. -->
      <!-- </p> -->


      <p>
        To finish  we need to put everything back in terms of
        <m>z</m>. 
        <!-- As before we<rsq/>ll be imposing conditions that will -->
        <!-- forestall the appearance of the absolute value so we will ignore -->
        <!-- it for the moment, and  assume that -->
        <!-- <me>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z} -->
        <!-- =\ln\left(\tan(\theta)+\sec(\theta)\right)+C </me>.   -->
        <!-- In fact, this -->
        <!-- is true as long as <m>\tan(\theta)+\sec(\theta)\ge 0</m>.   -->
        Once that is done we will 
        see what conditions need to be imposed to get rid of the absolute
        value that just popped up in the logarithm.
      </p>

      <p>
        <alert>Getting Everything Back in Terms of <m>z</m>. </alert>
        From our substitution we have <m>\tan(\theta)=z</m>, but what about
        <m>\sec(\theta)</m>?  We could certainly use <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPythTrigSecTan">equation</xref>, but this will lead to
        difficulties similar to the ones we tried to avoid by dropping the
        absolute value.  It is simpler to draw an appropriate triangle.
      </p>
      <p>
        In this case the appropriate triangle is the one with <m>\theta
        </m> in standard position. The beauty of this is that we
        don<rsq/>t need to know what the angle <m>\theta{}</m> is.  All we
        need to know is that <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{z}{1}</m>. Since in a
        right triangle <m>\tan( \theta ) =
        \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}}</m> we have this triangle:
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="FIGURETrigIdent">
        <caption>Diagram of a right triangle  where <m>\tan (\theta ) =z</m>
        and <m>0\le \theta \le \frac{\pi }{2}</m></caption>
        <image source="IC/zeqtan.png" width="40%">
          <shortdescription>Diagram of a right
          triangle with angle theta in standard position.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>



      <p>
        Since we<rsq/>ve got two sides of a right triangle we
        can compute the third side as shown.  And knowing the length of
        all three sides of a right triangle allows us to compute all of
        the trigonometic functions of <m>\theta</m>. So we have 

        <mdn>

          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONHangingSolution">\tan(\theta)=\frac{z}{1}=z\amp{}\amp{}
          \text{ and } \amp{}\amp{}\sec(\theta)=\frac{\sqrt{1+z^2}}{1}</mrow>
          </mdn>,
          which we can use to put our solution back in terms of <m>z</m>:
          <me>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}
          =\ln\abs{\tan(\theta)+\sec(\theta)}+C = \ln\abs{z + \sqrt{1+z^2}}+C</me>.  
          
      </p>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="FIGURETrigIdent"></xref> we placed <m>\theta </m> in
        the first quadrant which implicitly assumes that all of the
        trigonometric functions are positive. But we have no assurance that
        they are.  Any one of these values could be either positive or
        negative, depending on the value of <m>\theta </m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Working with a triangle like this will give us the right formula up to
        the algebraic sign.  That<rsq/>s why we called it a mnemonic and not a
        technique. Whether the values are positive or negative needs to be
        determined by you on a problem<ndash/>by<ndash/>problem basis. The
        good news is that you can wait until after you have computed the
        integral to make that determiniation.
      </p>


      <p>
        It is almost always easier to determine the values of the
        trigonometric functions by working from a mnemonic triangle than by
        using the various identites like <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPythSecTan">equation</xref> (which  were originally
        derived from the triangle anyway).
      </p>
      <p>
        We could also use 
        <xref ref="FIGURETrigIdent"></xref> to  obtain
        the formulas 
        <md>
          <mrow>\sin(\theta)\amp{} =\frac{z}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}, \amp{}\amp{}\amp{}\cos(\theta)
          \amp{}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}},</mrow>
          <mrow>\cot(\theta) \amp{}=\frac1z,\amp{}\amp{} \text{ and }\amp{}\csc(\theta) \amp{} =\frac{\sqrt{1+z^2}}{z}</mrow>
        </md>
        if we needed them.
      </p>
      <p>

        <alert> Dealing With the Absolute Value. </alert>
        <!-- <me>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\ln \abs{\tan \left(\theta \right) +\sec \left(\theta \right)}  +C</me>  -->
        First in terms of <m>z</m>, we have
        <me>
          \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\ln \abs{z+\sqrt{1+z^2}}+C
        </me>
      </p>

      <exercise>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              As clearly as you can, explain how you know that that
              that <m>z+\sqrt{1+z^2}\gt 0</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the result in part (a) to show that 
              <me>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\ln
              \left(z+\sqrt{1+z^2}\right)+C</me>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exercise>

      <p>
        So to re<ndash/>cap, we were trying to determine the solution
        to the hanging chain problem, which we had re<ndash/>cast as
        finding the solution the second order IVP
        <mdn>
          <mrow xml:id="IVPHangingChain">
          \dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+{\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)}^2}\amp{}\amp{}y(0)=0,\amp{}\amp{}\eval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x}{0}=0.</mrow>
        </mdn>
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Comment</title>
        <p>
          Because the differential
          equation involves the <term>second derivative</term> (is a
          second order equation) solving it will involve two
          integrations. Each integration will generate an arbitrary
          constant. That<rsq/>s why need two initial conditions; one
          for  each constant generated.
        </p>
      </aside>

      <p>
        Making the substitution <m>z=\dfdx{y}{x}</m> in <xref
        ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">equation</xref> gave us the
        equation
        <me>
          \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+z^2}
        </me> 
        and integrating both sides of that led to the equation
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONHangingChainFinal">
          \ln \left(z+\sqrt{1+z^2}\right)=\frac{w}{H}x+C
        </men> 
      </p>

      <exercise>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Recall that  the lowest point on the
              chain is at <m>(0,0)</m>.
              Use <xref
              ref="IVPHangingChain">IVP</xref> to show
              that <m>z\left(0\right)=0</m> so that
              <m>C=0</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use <xref
              ref="EQUATIONHangingChainFinal">equation</xref> to show that <m>z</m> must satisfy
              <me>\sqrt{1+z^2}=e^{\frac{w}{H}x}-z</me> 
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Square both sides of the result in part (b) to show that <m>z</m> must satisfy
              <me>2e^{\frac{w}{H}x}z={\left(e^{\frac{w}{H}x}\right)}^2-1</me> 
              and ultimately
              <me>z=\frac{1}{2}\left(e^{\frac{w}{H}x}-e^{-\frac{w}{H}x}\right)</me> 
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>


      </exercise>
      <p>

        So, we<rsq/>ve reduced the original catenary problem (problem <xref ref="IVPHangingChain">IVP</xref> to solving the IVP

        <mdn>
          
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONHangingIVP">\dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{1}{2}\left(e^{\frac{w}{H}x}-e^{-\frac{w}{H}x}\right),
          \amp{}\amp{}y\left(0\right)=0</mrow> 

        </mdn>

      </p>


      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMHngChainDeriveSol">
        <title> The Solution of the Hanging Chain Problem</title>
        <idx><h>The Hanging Chain</h><h>Derivation of the Solution</h></idx>
        <p>
          Solve <xref ref="EQUATIONHangingIVP">IVP</xref> to (finally) show that the catenary satisfies
          <me>y=\frac{H}{2w}\left(e^{\frac{w}{H}x}+e^{-\frac{w}{H}x}\right)</me> 
        </p>
      </exercise>



