</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONTrigSubst">
  <title> Trigonometric (Inverse) Substitutions</title>
  <p>
    In the previous subsection we saw that the presence of <m>1+z^2</m>
    suggests using the substitution <m>z=\tan (\theta )</m> to compute
    the integral <m>\int \frac{1}{1+z^2}\dx{z}</m>. This is because of
    the similarity of the two formulas <m> 1+z^2</m>, and <m> 1+\tan^2
    (\theta) </m>, and the identity
    <me>
      1+\tan^2   (\theta )=\sec^2 (\theta )
      </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    There is a larger pattern here which we will investigate in this
    subsection.
  </p>


  <exercise xml:id="PursuitCurve1">
    <title>The Pursuit Problem</title>
    <introduction>

      <figure xml:id="FIGUREPursuitCurve">
        <caption>
          The Pursuit Curve.
        </caption>
        <image source="IC/PursuitCurve.png" width="60%">
          <shortdescription>
            On the Cartesian plane a vertical line marked L passes
            through the point (1,0). The point D is at coordinates
            (1,vt) on the line L. A curve s begins at the origin
            bends upward as it approaches the line L. The point C is
            marked on s at coordinates (x,y). A ray tangent to s
            begins at (x,y) an points to D.
          </shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Suppose a cat <m>C</m>, starts running along the line
        <m>L</m> in the figure at a constant speed <m>v</m>.  When
        the cat reaches the point <m>(1,0)</m>, a dog <m>D</m>,
        starts chasing the cat by running directly at it.  Assuming
        that the dog travels at a speed which is <m>k</m> times the
        speed of the cat (where <m>k\gt1</m>) and always runs
        directly at the cat, find the path that the dog traverses.
        Such a path is called a pursuit curve.  The diagram in <xref
        ref="FIGUREPursuitCurve"></xref> shows the situation at time
        <m>t</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>s</m> denote the distance the dog has traveled
          along its path at time <m>t</m>. Show that the dog<rsq/>s
          path must satisfy the IVP

          <mdn>
            <mrow xml:id="PursuitEquation1">
              \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{\frac{s}{k}-y}{1-x},\amp{}\amp{}
              y(0)=0.
            </mrow>
          </mdn>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          You<rsq/>ll need to compare a differential triangle and an
          ordinary triangle, neither of which is shown in the
          figure.
        </p>
      </hint>

    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In order to solve for <m>y</m> it is tempting to rearrange <xref
          ref="PursuitEquation1">equation</xref> algebraically. But
          then we would have <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>,
          <m>s</m>, and <m>\dfdx{y}{x}</m> which isn<rsq/>t very
          helpful. The <m>s</m> term is particularly problematic
          since we know almost nothing about it.
        </p>
        <p>
          But only almost. Since <m>s</m> is the arc<ndash/>length
          of the dog<rsq/>s path we know that <m>\dx{s}</m> is the
          hypotenuse of a differential triangle so,
          <me>\dx{s}^2=\dx{x}^2+\dx{y}^2</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides of <xref
          ref="PursuitEquation1">equation</xref> with respect to
          <m>x</m> and  show that the
          dog<rsq/>s path must satisfy the differential equation

          <me>(1-x)\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{1}{k}\dfdx{s}{x}</me>

          so that

          <men xml:id="EQUATIONPursuitIVPSecondOrder">
            (1-x)\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}
            =\frac1k\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}
            </men>.
            
        </p>

      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          To differentiate the right side of <xref
          ref="PursuitEquation1">equation</xref> clearly requires
          the <xref ref="THEOREMQuotientRule" text="custom">Quotient
          Rule</xref>. Only one of the parameters is a constant. all
          the rest depend on <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain how you know that the initial conditions 

          <md>
            <mrow>y(0)=0,\amp{}\amp{}\text{ and }\amp{}\amp{}\dfdxat{y}{x}{0}=0</mrow>
          </md>
          are true. As in <xref ref="IVPHangingChain">IVP</xref> there are two initial
          conditions because solving <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPursuitIVPSecondOrder">equation</xref> for
          <m>y(x)</m>
          requires two integrations.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Because <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPursuitIVPSecondOrder">equation</xref>
          involves the second derivative of <m>y</m> it is hard
          to think about. We<rsq/>ll make it a little easier on
          our eyes with a substitution.
        </p>
        <p>
          Show that with the substitution 
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONPursuitReduceOrder">
            z=\dfdx{y}{x} 
          </men>
          <xref ref="EQUATIONPursuitIVPSecondOrder">equation</xref> becomes
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONPursuitEquation2">
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\frac1k\cdot\frac{1}{1-x}\dx{x}
          </men>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <!-- <task> -->
    <!--   <statement> -->
    <!--     <p> -->
    <!--       We will need an initial condition for                           <xref -->
    <!--       ref="EQUATIONPursuitIVPSecondOrder">equation</xref> before -->
    <!--       we can solve it for <m>z(x)</m>. -->
    <!--     </p> -->
    <!--     <p> -->
    <!--       Explain how you know that -->
    <!--       <m>z(0)=\eval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x}{0}=0</m>. -->
    
    <!--       <mdn> -->
    <!--         <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPursuitSolutionZ"> -->
    <!--           \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}\amp{}=\frac1k\cdot\frac{1}{1-x}, -->
    <!--         \amp{} z(0)\amp{}=0</mrow> -->
    <!--       </mdn>           -->
    <!--     </p> -->
    <!--   </statement> -->
    <!-- </task> -->
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use one of the initial conditions from part (c) and the
          trigonometric substitution <m>z=\tan(\theta)</m> in <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPursuitEquation2">equation</xref> to show
          that
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONPursuitSol">
            z=\frac12\left(\left(1-x\right)^{\frac{-1}{k}}-\left(1-x\right)^{\frac1k}\right){}
          </men>
          is the solution of <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPursuitEquation2">IVP</xref>. 
          Once again we  impose the condition <m>\frac{\pi }{2}\lt
          \theta \lt \frac{\pi }{2}</m> to ensure that we
          don<rsq/>t have to fuss with the Absolute Value.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use equations <xref
          ref="EQUATIONPursuitReduceOrder"></xref> and <xref ref="EQUATIONPursuitSol"></xref>   to show that the
          dog<rsq/>s path is the graph of the function
          <me>
            y=\frac{k}{2}\left[\frac{(1-x)^{\frac{k+1}{k}}}{k+1}+\frac{(1-x)^{\frac{k-1}{k}}}{k-1}\right]+\frac{k}{k^2-1}
            </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the <m>(x,y)</m> coordinates of the point where
          the dog catches the cat?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>






  <exercise xml:id="TractrixProblem1">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Of course, the tangent function is not the only
        trigonometric function at our disposal.  The following is
        the view from above of a tractor<ndash/>trailer.
        Initially, the center of the front axle of the tractor is
        at the origin and the center of the rear axle is at the
        point <m>(1,0)</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>Sketch of a tractor<ndash/>trailer in the act of
        turning.</caption>
        <image source="IC/Tractrix.png" width="80%">
          <shortdescription>Sketch of a tractor-trailer in the act
          of turning.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Suppose the tractor pulls the front wheels upward along
        the <m>y</m><ndash/>axis (the line <m>x=0</m>) and that
        the rear wheels don<rsq/>t slip.
      </p>


    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show the path that the center of the rear axle of the
          trailer follows must satisfy the IVP
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{-\sqrt{1-x^2}}{x}, \amp{}\amp{} y(1)=0.
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation, <m>y=y(x)</m> of the tractrix.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          After you separate the variables make the substitution
          <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m> and impose the condition <m>0\lt
          \theta \lt \frac{\pi }{2}</m>. This ensures that
          <me>\sqrt{1-\sin^2( \theta )}=\abs{\cos (\theta )}=\cos
          (\theta )</me> because it forces <m>0\lt x\lt 1</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Plot your solution on the <m>x-y</m> plane.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>DIGRESSION: Why Simplify When You Can Complicate?</title>


    <blockquote>
      <p>
        I never once failed at making a light bulb. I just found out 99 ways not to make one.
      </p>
      <attribution>
        <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Edison" visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Edison">Thomas A. Edison</url> (1847<ndash/>1931)
      </attribution>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      The idea of making substitutions like <m>x=\tan(\theta ) </m>
      or <m>x=\sin( \theta )</m> goes against everything we<rsq/>ve
      ever said about substitution. We<rsq/>ve always said that by
      substituting we were
      making things <q>easier on the eyes,</q> meaning of course
      that we were making things look simpler. But setting
      <m>z=\tan( \theta )</m> to turn <m>\int
      \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}</m> into
      <m>\int\frac{\sec^2(\theta )}
      {\sqrt{1+\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}</m> as we did in <xref
      ref="EQUATIONInvSubst1">equation</xref> hardly seems to be
      making anything simpler. If anything it looks more
      complicated.
    </p>
    <p>
      But remember that our over<ndash/>arching goal is always to
      solve the problem in front of us. If some substitution makes
      things <q>easier on the eyes</q> that<rsq/>s nice, but the
      real question is <q>Does it help solve the problem?</q> A
      <q>simplification</q> that doesn<rsq/>t help solve the problem
      is really a complication in a disguise. And a complication
      that allows you to (eventually) solve your problem is really a
      simplification in disguise. Don<rsq/>t reject a simplification
      just because it seems to make things more complicated at
      first. Take it another step or two and see what happens.
    </p>
    <p>
      This will sometimes feel as if you are wasting your time but
      you are not. Time spent thinking about your problem is always
      time well spent, even if it doesn<rsq/>t yield immediate
      results. When solving any problem you always have to try
      something that don<rsq/>t work (often several
      <q>somethings</q>) before you find something that does. That
      it is hard to do now is a testament to how far you<rsq/>ve
      come. The easy problems are behind you.
    </p>
    <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
  </paragraphs>



  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   <alert>THE REST OF THIS SECTION NEEDS TO BE REORGANIZED </alert> -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <p>
    There is one more trigonometric substitution that you should know. 
    When dealing with <m>\sqrt{x^2-1}</m>, it is often advantageous to
    let <m>x=\sec (\theta )</m> so that

    <me>
      \sqrt{x^2-1}=\sqrt{\sec^2 \left(\theta \right)-1}=\abs{\tan
      (\theta )} </me>.

      In order to free ourselves from the complications of the
      absolute value we restrict <m>\theta </m> to the values in
      <m>\left[0,\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\cup
      \left[\pi,\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)</m>.  This will ensure that
      <m>x</m> can take on any value in <m>\left(-\infty
      ,-1\right]\cup [1,\infty )</m>, while still guaranteeing that
      <m>\tan\left(\theta \right)\ge 0</m> so that
      <m>\sqrt{x^2-1}=\abs{\tan \left(\theta \right)}=\tan (\theta
      )</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is both cumbersom and confusing to keep track of the
    restrictions on <m>\theta </m> in each of these
    substitutions. So in practice we will simply  suppress all of that  and
    just say that for integrals

    <md>
      <mrow>
        \text{involving }1-x^2,
        \amp{}\amp{} 
        \text{ we let } x=\sin\left(\theta \right)
        \amp{}\amp{}
        \text{ so that }\sqrt{1-x^2}=\cos(\theta),
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        \text{involving }1+x^2, 
        \amp{}\amp{}
        \text{ we let }x=\tan(\theta )
        \amp{}\amp{}
        \text{ so that }\sqrt{1+x^2}=\sec(\theta ),
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        \text{involving } x^2-1,
        \amp{}\amp{}
        \text{ we let }x=\sec (\theta )
        \amp{}\amp{}
        \text{ so that }\sqrt{x^2-1}=\tan (\theta ),
      </mrow>
    </md>

    with the understanding that <m>\theta </m> was chosen in a
    manner which makes it unnecessary to fuss over any absolute
    values that might come up.
  </p>
  <p>
    There is an easy mnemonic to help you remember these
    substitutions. Notice that the expession <m>1-x^2</m> appears in
    the derivative of <m>\inverse\sin(x)</m>, and that when
    <m>1-x^2</m> appears you make the substitution <m>x=\sin( \theta
    )</m> (not <m>\inverse \sin (x )</m>; that<rsq/>s a different
    function). Similarly <m>1+x^2</m> appears in the derivative of
    <m>\inverse \tan( x )</m> and <m>x^2-1</m> appears in the
    derivative of <m>\inverse \sec( x)</m>.
  </p>



  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   As we have seen, it is the similarity of the formulas  -->

  <!--   <md> -->
  <!--     <mrow>1+z^2 \amp{}\amp{}  \text{and} \amp{}\amp{}1+\tan^2(\theta )</mrow>  -->

  <!--   </md> -->
  <!--   that suggested the substitution <m>z=\tan (\theta )</m> in the -->
  <!--   first place. They may not look similar to you at first, but look -->
  <!--   again more closely. Both have the form -->
  <!--   <m>1+(\text{something})^2</m>.  -->
  <!--   <!-\- In the first the <q>something</q> is <m>z</m> -\-> -->
  <!--   <!-\- in the second the <q>something</q> is<m>\tan(\theta)</m>. Because we -\-> -->
  <!--   <!-\- are familiar with <xref ref="EQUATIONPythSecTan"></xref> we can see -\-> -->
  <!--   <!-\- that there is  reason to hope that by making this change we will -\-> -->
  <!--   <!-\- eventually be able to generate an integral we can do. -\-> -->
  <!--   The two <q>somethings,</q> of course, are <m>z</m> and <m>\tan -->
  <!--   (\theta )</m>. -->
  <!--   If we set them equal then the two formulas are the same. And -->
  <!--   because we also know that  -->
  <!--   <me>1+\tan^2 (\theta )=\sec^2 (\theta )</me>  -->
  <!--   we can begin to simplify the integrand immediately after making -->
  <!--   the substitution.  -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   The sheer number of trig identities available to as tools make them -->
  <!--   a rich source of potential substitutions. -->

  <!-- </p> -->

  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   Let<rsq/>s examine this in a more familiar context. Because we -->
  <!--   know that <me>\dfdx{\left(\inverse \tan -->
  <!--   (x)\right)}{x}=\frac{1}{1+x}</me> we also know that that <me>\int -->
  <!--   \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x} = \inverse\tan(x) +C </me>, -->
  <!--   which  is  entry #12 of <xref -->
  <!--   ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>.  -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   But if we did not know this we could compute this integral -->
  <!--   directly by making the substitution -->
  <!--   <me>x=\tan (\theta )</me>,  -->
  <!--   <me> \dx{x}= \sec^2 (\theta )\dx{\theta{}}</me> as follows. -->
  <!--   <md> -->
  <!--     <mrow>\int \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x} \amp{}= \int -->
  <!--     \frac{1}{1+\tan^2} \sec^2 (\theta)\dx{\theta } )</mrow> -->
  <!--     <mrow> -->
  <!--       \amp{}=\int \frac{\sec^2 (\theta )}{\sec^2 (\theta )}\dx{\theta } -->
  <!--     </mrow> -->
  <!--     <mrow> -->
  <!--       \amp{}=\int \dx{\theta }=\theta +C. -->
  <!--     </mrow> -->
  <!--   </md> -->
  <!--   Since <m>x=\inverse\tan (\theta )</m> when we      put this back -->
  <!--   in terms of <m>x</m> we have  -->
  <!--   <me>\int \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x} = \inverse\tan (x)+C</me>. -->
  <!--   Thus the presence of the expression <m>1+x^2</m> suggests that -->
  <!--   the substitution <m>x=\tan (\theta )</m> might be helpful. -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <example xml:id="EXAMPLETrigSubstTan">
    <p>
      If we make the substitution <m>x=\tan (\theta
      )</m>, <m>\dx{x}=\sec^2 (\theta )</m> in the integral
      <m>\int \frac{1}{(1+x^2)^2}\dx{x}</m> we get
      <mdn>
        <mrow number="no">\int \frac{1}{(1+x^2)^2}\dx{x} \amp{}= \int
        \frac{1}{\sec^2 (\theta )}\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
        <mrow number="no">
          \amp{}=\int \cos^2 (\theta )\dx{\theta }.
        </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONIntCosSq1">
          \amp{}= \frac12 \theta +\frac14 \sin
          (2\theta ) +C 
        </mrow>
      </mdn>
      You will confirm <xref
      ref="EQUATIONIntCosSq1">equation</xref> in <xref
      ref="PROBLEMIntCosSqr"></xref>. From there it is
      straightforward to show that if <m>x=\tan (\theta )</m>, then

      <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntCosSq2">
        \int \frac{1}{(1+x^2)^2}\dx{x} =          \int \cos^2 (\theta )\dx{\theta }
        </men>.
        
    </p>
    <!--      <p> -->
    <!--        so that  -->
    <!--        <me> -->
    <!-- \frac12 \theta +\frac14 \sin -->
    <!-- (2\theta )+C -->
    <!--        </me> -->
    <!--      </p> -->
    <p>
      Now all that is left is to put everything back in terms of
      <m>x</m> which we will leave to you in <xref
      ref="PROBLEMCompleteExampleProb"></xref>.
    </p>
  </example> 
  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMCompleteExampleProb">

    <statement>

      <p>
        Complete  <xref
        ref="EXAMPLETrigSubstTan"></xref> by 
        using
        the substitution <m>x=\tan (\theta )</m> to show that 
        <me>
          \frac12 \theta + \frac14 \sin (2\theta ) =
          \frac12\left(\inverse\tan(x) +\frac{x}{1+x^2}\right)
          </me>.
      </p>

    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        You will need the Double<ndash/>Angle formula for the sine function from Trigonometry.
      </p>
    </hint>

  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMIntCosSqr">

    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that <me>\int \cos^2 (\theta )\dx{\theta }=\frac12 \theta
        +\frac14 \sin (2\theta )+C
      </me>
      as we stated in <xref ref="EXAMPLETrigSubstTan"></xref>. 
      </p>

    </statement>

    <hint>
      <p>
        Recall the Half<ndash/>Angle formula from Trigonometry:
        <me>\cos^2(x) = \frac12 \left( 1+\cos(2x)\right)</me>
      </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMTrigSubstCosSec">

    <statement>

      <p>
        From entry #11 and #13 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> we know that 
        <me>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin (x)+C</me>
        and
        <me>\int \frac{1}{\abs{x}\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec
        (x)+C</me>.
        Emulate our discussion in <xref
        ref="EXAMPLETrigSubstTan"></xref> to compute these integrals
        directly. 
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}\amp{}\amp{}\text{ and }\amp{}
            \amp{} \int \frac{1}{\abs{x}\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}.
          </mrow>
        </md>

      </p>
      <p>
        To avoid complications caused by the absolute value assume
        that <m>0\le \theta \le \frac{\pi}{2}</m>, so that <m>\sec( \theta
        )\ge 0</m> when you make your substitution.
      </p>

    </statement>
  </exercise>


  <p>
    This is all well and good, but the forms <m>\sqrt{1-x^2}</m>,
    <m>\sqrt{1+x^2}</m>, and <m>\sqrt{x^2-1}</m> are all very
    specific. Can we use these substitutions for an integral like
    <m>
      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4+x^2}}\dx{x}</m>?
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course we can. We just need to rearrange it using Algebra
    first.  Observe that if we had a <m>1</m> where the <m>4</m> is
    we<rsq/>d be fine. Of course, we can<rsq/>t just change it. That
    would change the entire integral. But if we factor out the
    <m>4</m> we get
    <men xml:id="TrigSubst1">
      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4+x^2}}\dx{x} =
      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\left(1+\frac{x^2}{4}\right)}}\dx{x} =
      \frac12\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^2}}\dx{x}  
      </men>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course, now we have another problem. We have
    <m>\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^2</m> where we were happy to have
    <m>x^2</m> before. But since we were going to substitute
    <m>x</m> away anyhow we<rsq/>ll just substitute <m>\frac{x}{2}</m>
    away instead.
  </p>
  <p>
    Letting <m>\frac{x}{2}=\tan(\theta)</m>, we proceed as before.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="TrigSubst2">
    
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Show that the antiderivative given are correct.
      </p>
    </introduction>


    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Finish computing the integral in <xref
          ref="TrigSubst1">equation</xref> and show that it is equal
          to <m>\inverse\sin\left( \frac{x}{2}\right) +C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{5-x^2}}\dx{x} = \inverse\sin
          \left(
          \frac{x}{\sqrt{5}}
          \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-9}}\dx{x} = \ln 
          \left(
          x + \sqrt{x^2-9}
          \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      
      <hint>
        <p>
          If your solution doesn<rsq/>t look exactly like ours
          don<rsq/>t jump to the conclusion that you are wrong. It is
          possible to get two different<ndash/>looking antiderivatives
          which are actual equivalent. 
        </p>
      </hint>

    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-6x}}\dx{x}=\ln
          \left(
          x-3+\sqrt{x^2-6x}
          \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          This integral appears to be a completely different from
          the others in this problem, but it
          really isn<rsq/>t. Complete the square on <m>x^2-6x</m> and
          then use your result in part (c).
        </p>
      </hint>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   We have   seen that  -->
      <!--   <ul> -->
      <!--     <li> -->
      <!--       the -->
      <!--       presence of <m>1+x^2</m> suggests the substitution -->
      <!--       <m>x=\tan(x) </m>, -->
      <!--     </li> -->
      <!--     <li> -->
      <!--       the presence of <m>1-x^2</m> suggests the substitution -->
      <!--       <m>x=\sin(x) </m>, -->
      <!--     </li> -->
      <!--     <li> -->
      <!--       and the presence of <m>x^2-1</m> suggests -->
      <!--       the substitution <m>x=\sec(x) </m>. -->
      <!--     </li> -->
      <!--   </ul>  -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <p>
        Use the substitutions we have studied in this section to
        show that the antiderivatives given are correct. You may
        need to you may need to rearrange the integrand
        algebraically or make other substitutions first.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int
          \frac{8}{1+4x^2}\dx{x}=4\inverse\tan (2x)+
          C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int
          \frac{6}{\sqrt{1-9t^2}}\dx{t}=2\inverse\sin(3t)+C </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}} \dx{x} = \inverse\sec
          \left( 2x \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{2}{x(x^2-1)}\dx{x} = 2\ln\abs{\frac{x-1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}}+C </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{16+x^2}\dx{x}=
          \frac14\inverse\tan\left(\frac{x}{4}\right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\int\frac{6}{\sqrt{16-9x^2}}\dx{x} = 2\inverse\sin \left(
          \frac{3x}{4} \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{3+x^4}\dx{x}=
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{12}}\inverse\tan 
          \left(
          \frac{x^2}{\sqrt{12}}+C
          \right)              </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int
          \frac{e^{2t}}{\sqrt{5-e^{4t}}}\dx{t} = \frac12 \inverse
          \sin 
          \left(
          \frac{e^{2t}}{\sqrt{5}}
          \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task> 
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{x}(1-x)}\dx{x}=
          2\inverse\tan 
          \left(
          \sqrt{x}
          \right)+C</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{x}(x-1)}\dx{x}=2\ln\abs{\sqrt{x}-1}+C
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>




  </exercise>

  <!-- </subsection> -->


  <!--   <subsection> -->
  <!--     <title>Trigonometric Integrals</title> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   As you saw in <xref ref="SUBSECTIONTrigSubst"></xref> inverse -->
  <!--     substitution will sometimes generate an integral involving one -->
  <!--     or more of the trigonometric functions. Such integrals  are sometimes called -->
  <!--     <term>Trigonometric (or Trig) Integrals</term>. Although  we -->
  <!--     have given  -->
  <!--     them their own section and  heading they are intrinsically -->
  <!--     different from other integrals. It<rsq/>s just that the -->
  <!--     relations between the trigonometric functions are so many, and -->
  <!--     so varied that it is a little easier to learn to deal with -->
  <!--     them together. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     Substitution is the most powerful integration technique we have so -->
  <!--     a substitution should always be the first thing you try when faced -->
  <!--     with a new integral and the various trigonometric identities -->
  <!--     provide a rich source of possible substitutions. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
