  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   It should be clear from <xref ref="TrigSubst2"></xref> -->
  <!--   that as long as the expression inside the radical is a -->
  <!--   quadratic, we can manipulate it algebraically to produce -->
  <!--   something of the form -->
  <!--   <m>\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2}</m>, -->
  <!--   <m>\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2}</m>or -->
  <!--   <m>\sqrt{\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2-1}</m>.  From there, we -->
  <!--   can use the appropriate trigonometric substitution. -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <exercise xml:id="FallingWithDrag">
    <idx><h>Problem</h><h>Quadratic Drag</h></idx>
    <introduction>

      <p>
        In <xref ref="PROBLEMTerminalVelocity"></xref> we computed
        terminal velocity of an object falling with <term>linear
        drag</term>. Now we will consider <term>quadratic drag</term>
        and compare the two.
      </p>
      <p>
        An example of this would be a ball of mass <m>M</m> falling in
        air.  In this case buoyancy is typically negligible so we will
        disregard it. First, let <m>y(t)</m> be distance
        the ball has fallen (so the positive <m>y</m> axis is pointing
        downward), with <m>y(0)=0</m> representing the initial position
        of the ball. As always we denote the
        acceleration due to gravity by <m>g</m>, so the weight of the
        ball is <m>Mg</m>. Quadratic drag
        is proportional to the square of the velocity, so  <m>-Rv^2</m>,
        where <m>R</m> is a constant that will depend on the medium our
        ball is falling through (air, in this instance) and
        <m>v=\dfdx{v}{t}</m> is the velocity. For simplicity, we will
        assume <m>v(0)=0</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use Newton<rsq/>s Second Law of Motion:
          (<m>F</m>)<m>=</m>(<m>M</m>)ass<m>\cdot{}</m>(<m>A</m>)cceleration,
          to show that the velocity of the ball must satisfy the
          IVP:
          <mdn>
            <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONQuadraticDragIVP">              M\dfdx{v}{t}\amp{}=Mg-Rv^2,\amp{} v(0)\amp{}=0 </mrow>
          </mdn>
        </p>
        <p>
          Show that the IVP above is equivalent to
          <me>
            \frac{\dx{v}}{1-\frac{R}{Mg}v^2}=g\dx{t}, \hskip5mm
            v(0)=0 </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the substitution <m>\sqrt{\frac{R}{Mg}}v =
          \sin(\theta)</m> to show that 
          
          <me>
            v=\sqrt{\frac{Mg}{R}}\left[\frac{1-e^{-2gt}}{1+e^{-2gt}}\right]                      </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\limit{t}{\infty}{v}</m>. Compare this
          terminal velocity with our previous results.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

  </exercise>
  <example xml:id="EXAMPLEHigherOrderRoots1">
    <p>
      The trigonometric substitutions we<rsq/>ve dealt with so far have
      all involved square roots. What about this integral:
      <m>\int\frac{\dx{x}}{(1-x^2)^\frac32}</m>? Do you see that this
      is only slightly more complicated?
    </p>
    <p>
      If we make the substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m>, then
      <m>\dx{x}=\cos(\theta)</m> as before so,

      <md>
        <mrow>
          \int\frac{\dx{x}}{(1-x^2)^\frac32}\amp{}=
          \int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\left(\sqrt{1-\sin^2(\theta)}\right)^3}\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=\int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\cos^3(\theta)}\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=\int\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=\tan(\theta)+C 
        </mrow>
        <!-- <mrow> -->
        <!--   \amp{}=\int\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}=\tan(\theta)+C -->
        <!--   </mrow>. -->
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>\sin(\theta)=\frac{x}{2}</m>, we use the triangle
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Image of the triangle</caption>
      <image source="IC/TrigTri1.png" width="20%">
        <shortdescription>Image of the triangle with theta in
        standard position and legs x and square root of one - x
        squared.</shortdescription>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      so that, finally
      <me>
        \int\frac{\dx{x}}{\left(x^2-1\right)^\frac32}=\tan(\theta)+C=\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}+C
        </me>.
    </p>
  </example>

  <problem>
    <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
    <p>
      Confirm that <xref ref="EXAMPLEHigherOrderRoots1"></xref> this is
      correct by differentiating: <m>\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</m>.
    </p>
  </problem>

  <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEHigherOrderRoot2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        If we need to compute  integral
        <me>
          \int\frac{x}{\left(x^2-1\right)^\frac32}\dx{x}{}
          </me>?
          the substitution <m>x=\sec(\theta)</m> leads to:
          <m>\int{\frac{\sec(\theta)}{\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}</m>,
          which 
          we can rewrite as
          <md>
            <mrow>        \int{\frac{\sec(\theta)}{\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}\amp{}=\int\frac{1/\cos(\theta)}{\sin^2(\theta)/\cos^2(\theta)}\dx{\theta}</mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{}=\int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin^2(\theta)}\dx{\theta}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{}=\int\cot(\theta)\csc(\theta)\dx{\theta}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{}=-\csc(\theta)+C
            </mrow>
          </md>
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Complete this integral by showing
          that <me>-\csc(\theta ) = \frac{-x}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}</me>.
        </p>

      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find another substitution that works, compute the integral again
          using your new substitution, and show that the antiderivative you
          obtain is equivalent to the antiderivative in part (a).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

  </exercise>

  <p>
    In the beginning computing an  integral appears to be essentially a
    trial and error kind of thing. But there are some
    standard tricks to learn. It is probably best to learn these
    tricks by working through specific examples.  As you work through
    these problems 
    focus on the technique being used and how it might be adapted to 
    similar integrals, not the specific example we are working on.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="OddSinPower">
    
    <p>
      <me>
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
      </me>

      Since sine is raised to an odd power we<rsq/>ll
      <q>save one of the sines</q> and then convert everything else to
      cosines using the Pythagorean identity
      <me>\sin^2(\theta)+\cos^2(\theta)=1</me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      First we <q>save a sine.</q>
      <me>
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
        \int\sin(\theta)\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}=\int(1-\cos^2(\theta))\cos^2(\theta)\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>.  Next we let <m>z=\cos(\theta)</m>, so that
        <m>\dx{z}=-\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, which gives
        <md>
          <mrow>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} \amp =
          \int(1-z^2)z^2(-\dx{z})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp =\int(z^4-z^2)\dx{z}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp =\frac{z^5}{5}=\frac{z^3}{3}+c</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp
          =\frac{\cos^5(\theta)}{5}=\frac{\cos^3(\theta)}{3}+c</mrow>
          </md>.
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    Had the cosine been raised to an odd power in <xref
    ref="OddSinPower"></xref>, we could have <q>saved
    one of the cosines</q> instead.
  </p>
  

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Compute
      <m>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>.
    </p>
  </exercise>




  <example>
    <p>
      Notice that in <xref ref="OddSinPower"></xref> there
      would have been nothing wrong with computing
      <m>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> as
      follows:
      <md>
        <mrow>           \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} \amp{}=
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos(\theta)\cos(\theta)\dx{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\sqrt{1-\sin^2(\theta)}\cos(\theta)\dx{\theta}.</mrow>
      </md>
      It<rsq/>s just that it is not immediately clear how to
      continue from here.  Most people will shy away from this
      because of the square root but in fact, this integral can
      be computed using techniques you already know.
    </p>
    <p>
      First, the elementary substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m> will
      give:
      <me>
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} = \int
        x^3\sqrt{1-x^2}\dx{x} </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      You see why we wouldn<rsq/>t want to go this route, right? Recall
      that we introduced trigonometric substitutions precisely so
      we could handle integrals like this last one. It would seem
      to be counterproductive to take this path since we <em>
      started </em> with an integral involving trigonometric
      functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      While our goal is to be able to work out integrals by the
      simplest possible method, not the most difficult, it can
      instructive to see that a computation can be done in more
      than one manner so we will pursue this just a bit farther.
    </p>
  </example>
  <exercise>
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Compute the integral <m>\int x^3\sqrt{1-x^2}\dx{x}</m>
        using these substitutions:
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>u=1-x^2</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Finish <xref ref="OddSinPower">example</xref> using each of the
        substitutions in part (a) and part (b). Do you get the same
        solution as before? Explain.
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="SinCosOddPower">
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Compute the integral
        <m>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> by:
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Saving one of the cosines and converting everthing else
          into sines.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Saving one of the sines and converting everthing else
          into cosines.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Do you get the same result in parts (a) and (b)? Explain.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <example xml:id="EXAMPLESinCosEven">
    <p>
      What happens if you don<rsq/>t have an odd power of sine or
      cosine?  For example, suppose you have
      <m>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Note to self</title>
      <p>
        We may want to consider moving <xref
        ref="DIGRESSIONIntPolySecTan" text="custom"> Polynomials in
        secant and tangent</xref>  to just above this example.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      Saving a sine or cosine would lead to an integrand with a
      square root, which we are trying to avoid, if we can help
      it.
      In <xref ref="PROBLEMIntCosSqr"></xref> we saw that one of the
      Half<ndash/>Angle formulas from Trigonometry was helpful. 
      In fact, the  Half-Angle formlas:
      <me>
        \sin^2(\theta) = \frac12\left(1-\cos(2\theta)\right) \text{
        and } \cos^2(\theta)=\frac12\left(1+\cos(2\theta)\right)
      </me> 
      are just the tool we need when there is no way to <q>save</q> a
      sine or cosine.

      Using these identities in the integral
      <me>\int\sin^2( \theta )\cos^2 (\theta )\dx{x}    </me>
      we see that
      <md>
        <mrow>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}\amp
        =\frac14\int(1-\cos(2\theta))(1+\cos(2\theta))\dx{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =\frac14\int (1-\cos^2(2\theta))\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =\frac{1}{4}\int\sin^2(2\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      which doesn<rsq/>t seem to help much until we notice that we can
      use  the Half-Angle formula again. This gives
      <me>
        \frac{1}{4}\int\sin^2(2\theta)\dx{\theta} =
        \frac18\int(1-\cos(4\theta))\dx{\theta} =
        \frac18\left(\theta-\frac14\sin(4\theta)\right)+C
      </me>
    </p>
  </example>
  <problem>
    <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
    <p>
      Rewrite the integral in <xref
      ref="EXAMPLESinCosEven"></xref>  as 
      <me>\int(\left(\sin(\theta)\cos(\theta)\right)^2\dx{\theta }
      </me>
      and compute the integral again using the Double Angle
      formula: <m>\sin(2\theta)=2\sin(\theta)\cos(\theta)</m>.
      Show that you get an equivalent antiderivative.
    </p>
  </problem>
  <example>
    <p>
      <m>
        \int\sec^4(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this example, we can save a <m>\sec^2(\theta)</m> as part
      of the differential and use the identity
      <m>\sec^2(\theta)=1+\tan^2(\theta)</m> to change everything
      else into an expression in tangent. Since the secant is to an
      even power this again avoids square roots, which is the
      general idea.
      <md>
        <mrow>\int \sec^4(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}\amp
        =\int
        \sec^2(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>
          \int(1+\tan^2(\theta))\tan^2(\theta)\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      Letting <m>y=\tan(\theta)</m> we have
      <m>\dx{y}=\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, so we obtain

      <md>
        <mrow>\int(1+y^2)y^2\dx{y}=\int(y^2+y^4)\dx{y}=\frac{y^3}{3}+\frac{y^5}{5}+c=\frac{\tan^3(\theta)}{3}+\frac{\tan^5(\theta)}{5}+c</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </example>

  <example>
    <p>
      If tangent occurs to an odd power, we can save a tangent and
      a secant as part of the differential and use the same
      identity to convert everything else to secant.
      <me>
        \int\sec^2(\theta)\tan^3(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
        \int\sec^2(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)\dx{\theta{}}=\int\sec^2(\theta)(\sec^2(\theta)-1)\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>.  Letting <m>u=\sec(\theta)</m> we have
        <me>
          \int u^2(u^2-1)\dx{u}=\int
          (u^4-u^2)\dx{u}=\frac{u^5}{5}-\frac{u^3}{3}+c=\frac{\sec^5(\theta)}{5}-\frac{\sec^3(\theta)}{3}+c
          </me>.
    </p>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the integral
        <me>
          \int\sec^4(\theta)\tan^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute this integral by saving a <m>\sec^2(\theta)</m>
          and converting the rest into an expression in tangent.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute this integral by saving a
          <m>\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)</m> and converting the rest
          into an expression in secant.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Verify the at you get the same result in (a) and (b).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    

    <p>
      Previously we computed <m>\int \tan(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>
      using the identity
      <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin(\theta)}</m>. We
      could also use the identity
      <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)}{\sec(\theta)}\dx{\theta}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Do we get a different answer? Explain.
    </p>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    Integrals involving cosecant and cotangent will succomb to tricks
    similar to those we<rsq/>ve used for the secant and tangent, except
    that we need  identity <me>\csc^2(\theta)=1+\cot^2(\theta)</me>. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Obviously, we have not covered every type of integral that might
    occur.  We<rsq/>ve only provided some basics that you can build on
    as you gain experience. 
  </p>
  <p>
    As always the key to success is practice, practice, practice!.
  </p>

</subsection>
</section>




<section xml:id="SECTIONPartFrac">
  <title>  The  Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
  <subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONPFDSimple">
    <title>Simple Decompositions: The Logistic Equation,
    Redux</title>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Mathematics is the art of avoiding computation.
      </p>
      <attribution>
        <url href="https://ethw.org/Brockway_McMillan" visual="https://ethw.org/Brockway_McMillan">           Brockway McMillan
        </url>
      </attribution>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      When we analyzed the  <xref ref="EQUATIONLogEq" text="custom">Logistic Equation</xref>
      <!-- <men xml:id="LogisticGrowthFromDiffCalc"> -->
      <!--   \dfdx{y}{t}=.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)=0.0001(100-y) -->
      <!-- </men>.   -->
      in <xref ref="SECTIONpopulation-dynamics"></xref> we were
      unable to  find a formula for <m>P(t)</m>. But, by analyzing the IVP
      directly we were able to generate a <q>qualitative</q> graph
      of <m>P(t)</m>. That is, we were able to get a general sense
      of the shape of the graph of <m>P(t)</m> even if the
      coordinates of particular points were unavailable.
    </p>
    <p>
      While a qualitative graph is better than nothing, it would be
      more useful to have an explicit formula for <m>P(t)</m>, if we
      can find it. With integration we now have the tool we need to
      find such a formula.
    </p>

    <p>
      Starting with the Logistic Equation,
      <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONLogisticRedux">
          \dfdx{P}{t} \amp{}= 0.1P \left( 1-\frac{P}{100}
          \right),\amp{}P(0)\amp{}=10,
        </mrow>      
      </mdn>
      the first step is to  separate the
      variables:
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac1">
        \frac{\dx{P}}{P(100-P)}=0.001\dx{t}
        </men>. 
        If  we integrate both sides of this equation the result
        will be an equation in which  <m>P(t)</m> appears. If we can
        solve that for <m>P(t)</m> we will have our formula for
        <m>P(t)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Integrating the right sides presents no difficulties: 
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONLogisticLeftSide">\int 0.001\dx{t} = 0.001t+C</men>.
    </p>
    <p>
      But at our current level of skill with integration the only
      option that presents itself for integrating the left side is to
      to complete the square in the denominator and apply the
      appropriate trigonometric substitution.
    </p>





    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMLogisticTrigSubst">
      <statement>
        <p>
          By completing the square in the denominator and making the
          substitution <m>P-50=50\sin (\theta )</m> integrate
          the left side of <xref
          ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac1">equation</xref> and show
          that
          
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONLogisticTrigSubst">
            \frac{1}{50}\ln
            \left[
            \sqrt{\frac{100-P}{P}}
            \right]
            = 0.001t+C</men>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONLogisticEquation">
    <title>  Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover<ndash/>up Method (HCUM)</title>


    <p>
      As you have just seen, integrating the left side of <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac1">equation</xref>  is entirely within the
      range of our current skill set but it is rather daunting. And
      we<rsq/>re not even finished yet.  We must still solve <xref
      ref="EQUATIONLogisticTrigSubst">equation</xref> for
      <m>P(t)</m>. Before we do that we<rsq/>d really like to find a
      simpler way to compute the integral.
    </p>
    <p>

      To be consistent with what follows we observe that we can
      rewrite <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac1">equation</xref> as

      <men>
        \frac{\dx{P}}{P\left(P-100\right)}=-0.001 \dx{t}
      </men> 
      since <m>\frac{\dx{P}}{P\left(P-100\right)} =
      -\frac{\dx{P}}{P\left(100-P\right)}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Integrating the right<ndash/>hand side poses no problem as we
      would get
        
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFD6">\int{\frac{\dx{P}}{P\left(P-100\right)}}=-0.001\ t+C</men> 

      To compute the left<ndash/>hand side, notice that
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFD4">\frac{1}{P\left(P-100\right)}=\frac{-\frac{1}{100}}{P}+\frac{\frac{1}{100}}{P-100}</men> 
    </p>



      <exercise>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Confirm <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD4">equation</xref>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD4">equation</xref> to show that
            <me>\int{\frac{\dx{P}}{P\left(P-100\right)}}=\frac{1}{100}{\mathrm{ln} \left(\frac{P-100}{P}\right)\ }+C_2</me>       </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD6">equation</xref> and the  result in  part (b) to show that 
              <me>P\left(t\right)=\frac{100}{1+Ke^{-0.1t}}</me> 
              where <m>K</m> is an arbitrary constant.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticTrigSubst">equation</xref>
              for <m>P</m> and show you obtain the same result.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The original <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticRedux">IVP</xref> had the initial
              condition <m>P\left(0\right)=10</m>.  Use this to show that
              <m>K=9</m> and plot this graph to confirm that it has the same
              general shape that we discovered in Subsection 11.1.1
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exercise>
      <p>

        This is certainly easier to deal with than a trigonometric
        substitution, but it begs the question, <q>Where did <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPFD4">equation</xref>
        <m>\frac{1}{P\left(P-100\right)}=-\frac{\frac{1}{100}}{P}+\frac{\frac{1}{100}}{P-100}</m>
        come from?</q> It is one thing to verify such an identity, but
        it is quite another to actually formulate one.
      </p>

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Here<rsq/>s a simpler way. Observe that the fraction -->
      <!--   <m>\frac{1}{P(100-P)}</m> can be decomposed as  -->
      <!--   <men xml:id="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac2"> -->
      <!--     \frac{1}{P(100-P)}=\frac{\frac{-1}{100}}{P}+\frac{\frac{1}{100}}{100-P} -->
      <!--     </men>.  -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <!-\- <problem xml:id="DRILLLogisticPartFrac2"> -\-> -->
      <!-- <!-\-   <p> -\-> -->
      <!-- <!-\-     Confirm <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac2">equation</xref>. -\-> -->
      <!-- <!-\-   </p> -\-> -->
      <!-- <!-\- </problem> -\-> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   With <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac2">the identity</xref> -->
      <!--   in hand we can integrate the right side of <xref -->
      <!--   ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac1">equation</xref> as follows. -->

      <!--   <md> -->
      <!--     <mrow>\int \frac{1}{P(100-P)}\dx{x} \amp{}= -->
      <!--     \int\frac{\frac{1}{100}}{P}+\frac{\frac{1}{100}}{100-P}\dx{x} </mrow> -->
      <!--     <mrow> -->
      <!--       \amp{}= -->
      <!--       \frac{1}{100} -->
      <!--       \left[ -->
      <!--       -\ln\left(\frac{1}{P}\right)+\ln\left(\frac{1}{100-P}\right) -->
      <!--       \right] -->
      <!--     </mrow> -->
      <!--     <mrow> -->
      <!--       \amp{}=  \frac{1}{100} -->
      <!--       \ln  -->
      <!--       \left( -->
      <!--       \frac{P}{100-P} -->
      <!--       \right) -->
      <!--     </mrow> -->

      <!--   </md> -->
      <!--   Combining this with <xref -->
      <!--   ref="EQUATIONLogisticLeftSide">equation</xref> we see that <men -->
      <!--   xml:id="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac3"> -\frac{1}{100} \ln \left( -->
      <!--   \frac{100-P}{P} \right) = \int 0.0001\dx{t} = 0.0001t+C</men> -->
      <!--   which is much easier to solve for <m>P(t)</m> than  <xref -->
      <!--   ref="EQUATIONLogisticTrigSubst">equation</xref>.  -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <exercise> -->
      <!--   <task> -->
      <!--     <statement> -->
      <!--       <p> -->
      <!--         Confirm <xref ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac2">equation</xref>. -->
      <!--       </p> -->
      <!--     </statement> -->
      <!--   </task> -->
      <!--   <task> -->
      <!--     <statement> -->
      <!--       <p> -->
      <!--         Use the result of part (a) to show -->
      <!--         that  -->
      <!--         <me>\int \frac{\dx{P}}{P(100-P)}=-\frac{1}{100}\ln  -->
      <!--         \left( -->
      <!--         \frac{100-P}{P} -->
      <!--         \right)+C_2</me> -->
      <!--         <!-\- <m>P(t) = \frac{100}{Ke^{-0.01t}+1}</m> where <m>K</m> is an -\-> -->
      <!--         <!-\- arbitrary constant. -\-> -->
      <!--       </p> -->
      <!--     </statement> -->
      <!--   </task> -->
      <!--   <task> -->
      <!--     <statement> -->
      <!--       <p> -->
      <!--         Use the result of part (b) to show that <xref -->
      <!--         ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac1">equation</xref> -->
      <!--         yields -->
      <!--         <me>P(t)=\frac{100}{1+Ke^{-0.001t}}</me> where <m>K</m> -->
      <!--         is an arbitrary constant.  -->
      <!--       </p> -->
      <!--     </statement> -->
      <!--   </task> -->
      <!--   <task> -->
      <!--     <statement> -->
      <!--       <p> -->
      <!--         Use the  -->
      <!--         initial condition in <xref -->
      <!--         ref="EQUATIONLogisticRedux">IVP</xref> to show -->
      <!--         that in part (c) -->
      <!--         <m>K=9</m>,  -->
      <!--         and then confirm that you get the same solution when you -->
      <!--         solve <xref -->
      <!--         ref="EQUATIONLogisticTrigSubst">equation</xref> for -->
      <!--         <m>P(t)</m>. -->
      <!--       </p> -->
      <!--     </statement> -->
      <!--   </task> -->
      <!--   <task> -->
      <!--     <statement> -->
      <!--       <p> -->
      <!--         Graph <m>P(t)</m> from part (c) and confirm that it -->
      <!--         has the same general shape that we discovered in <xref -->
      <!--         ref="SUBSECTIONModelingTrout"></xref>. -->
      <!--       </p> -->
      <!--     </statement> -->
      <!--   </task> -->
      <!-- </exercise> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   This is much simpler but the roadblock is this: where did <xref -->
      <!--   ref="EQUATIONLogisticPartFrac2">equation</xref> come from? How did -->
      <!--   we find this decomposition of the fraction -->
      <!--   <m>\frac{1}{P(100-P)}</m>? -->
      <!-- </p> -->


      <p>
        We found <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD4">equation</xref> by
        an algebraic technique called the <term>Partial Fraction
        Decomposition </term> or <term>PFD</term>. There are several
        places in mathematics where it is useful to break a single
        rational expresstion into the sum of simpler rational
        expressions. We will be using  it to simplify  the integration 
        when the integrand is a rational function. 
      </p>
      <p>
        A fully general statement of the PFD is given in <xref
        ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref> but as you can see
        the general statement is quite comprehensive. Moreover the
        statement of the theorem doesn<rsq/>t help us use it as a
        practical tool. So we will work through a number of increasingly
        complex examples to build things up slowly.
      </p>
      <p>
        To begin, if we have an expression of the form
        <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}</m> where <m>a</m>, and <m>b</m> are
        known constants, and <m>a\neq b</m>, then the PFD says that there are constants
        <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> such that as
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDDegrees">\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}</men>. Our
        task is to find values for <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Take note of the following fact: The right side of <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPFDDegrees">equation</xref> consists of rational
        functions where the degree of the numerator is one less than
        the degree of the denominator. Since the numerators are all
        constants (polynomials of degree zero) and the denominators
        are all linear (polynomials of degree one) this is, at the
        moment, a rather bombastic way to state this fact. However in <xref
        ref="SUBSECTIONPFDNonSimple"></xref> we will find it
        very useful.
      </p>

      <p>
        There are a couple of ways we can find <m>A</m> and
        <m>B</m>. What we<rsq/>d like to do is find the simplest, least
        difficult to implement method we can. After all, we<rsq/>re not
        here to do fraction decompositions. This is just one step toward
        computing an integral and we<rsq/>d like for the decomposition
        step to be as simple and painless as possible.
      </p>
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Conceptually the simplest method available is to simply to choose -->
      <!--   values for <m>x</m>.  -->
      <!--   This is a valid approach because the equation -->
      <!--   <me>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}</me>  -->
      <!--   is actually an identity <mdash/> it will be true no matter what -->
      <!--   the value of <m>x</m> is.  -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   If we choose <m>x=0</m> we get <me> Ab+Ba =-1</me>, and if we -->
      <!--   choose <m>x=1</m> we get <me>\frac{1}{(1-a)(1-b)}=\frac{A}{1-a} -->
      <!--   + \frac{B}{1-b}</me> and we have a system of two equations in -->
      <!--   the unknowns <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> which we can solve. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <problem xml:id="DRILLPFD2x2-1"> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     In this form the equations <me> Ab+Ba =-1</me> and, -->
      <!--     <me>\frac{1}{(1-a)(1-b)}=\frac{A}{1-a} + \frac{B}{1-b}</me> -->
      <!--     are a little intimidating. But it<rsq/>s not really as bad as -->
      <!--     it looks. Clear the fractions and then solve for <m>A</m> and -->
      <!--     <m>B</m>. -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!-- </problem> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   The method we<rsq/>ve just outlined will work, and it will always -->
      <!--   work.  But this is only our first example of the PFD and you can -->
      <!--   surely see that that if we have more than two constants the difficulty of -->
      <!--   solving for the coefficients will increase rapidly. But again, this method -->
      <!--   works and it will always work, so it is something we can always fall back -->
      <!--   on if we can<rsq/>t find something simpler. -->
      <!-- </p> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Since the method just outlined will always work one possible way -->
      <!--   to lighten the load is to look for values of <m>x</m> that will -->
      <!--   make the resulting equations simpler to solve.  Sadly, no -->
      <!--   obvious choice presents itself, but hold that thought for a -->
      <!--   bit. We<rsq/>ll return to it. -->
      <!-- </p> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Another possible method is to simply clear the fractions and -->
      <!--   compare like terms. (In fact, our previous method can be made -->
      <!--   a little more palatable by clearing the fractions first.) Thus -->
      <!--   <me> -->
      <!--     (x-a)(x-b)\cdot\left[\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}\right]=\left[ -->
      <!--     \frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}\right]\cdot(x-a)(x-b) -->
      <!--     </me>. -->
      <!--     Multiplying through and cancelling, we have -->

      <!--     <men  xml:id="EQUATIONPFD1"> -->
      <!--       1=A(x-b)+B(x-a) -->
      <!--     </men> -->
      <!--     so that -->
      <!--     <me> -->
      <!--       \textcolor{red}{0}x+ \textcolor{blue}{1}=(\textcolor{red}{A+B})x + \left(\textcolor{blue}{-Ab-aB}\right)   -->
      <!--       </me>. -->
      <!--       Comparing the coefficient of <m>x</m> -->
      <!--       and the constant terms we see that we need to solve  the following system of -->
      <!--       two equations in the two unknowns <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> -->
      <!--       <mdn> -->
      <!--         <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPFD2">A+B\amp{}=0</mrow> -->
      <!--         <mrow number="no"> -->
      <!--           Ab+Ba \amp{}=-1. -->
      <!--         </mrow> -->
      <!--       </mdn> -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <problem xml:id="DRILLDRILLPFD2x2-2" > -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     Solve the <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD2">system of equations</xref> -->
      <!--     and show that you get the same solution that you got in <xref -->
      <!--     ref="DRILLPFD2x2-1"></xref>. -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!-- </problem> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   This is a little better. We<rsq/>ve still got a system of two -->
      <!--   equations to solve, but it seems to be a little more -->
      <!--   manageable. Still, as the problems get more complex the number -->
      <!--   of equations in our system will grow. We<rsq/>d still like to -->
      <!--   find something simpler than this if we can. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   But wait! Take another look at <xref -->
    <!--   ref="EQUATIONPFD1">equation</xref>. With a judicious use of that -->
    <!--   formula you can actually compute this PFD almost completely in -->
    <!--   your head. It<rsq/>s that simple. Really. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Because <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD1">equation</xref> is an -->
    <!--   identity, <mdash/> it is true regardless of which value of -->
    <!--   <m>x</m> we choose.  So of we choose <m>x=a</m> we get -->
    <!--   <me>A=\frac{1}{a-b}</me> immediately. Similarly choosing -->
    <!--   <m>x=b</m> gives <m> B=\frac{1}{b-a}</m>, also -->
    <!--   immediately.Thus the PFD of <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}</m> is -->
    <!--   <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFD3">\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}= -->
    <!--   \frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{b-a}}{x-b}</men>. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <problem> -->
    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     Verify the  -->
    <!--     <xref ref="EQUATIONPFD3">identity</xref>  by adding -->
    <!--     the fractions on the right side together. -->
    <!--   </p> -->
    <!-- </problem> -->

    <!-- <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPFDSimplestForm"> -->
    <!--   <title>The PFD in its Simplest Form (Find the Pattern)</title> -->
    <!--   <idx><h>Partial Fraction Decomposition</h><h> simplest form of the PFD </h></idx> -->
    <!--   <introduction> -->
    <!--     <p> -->
    <!--       We<rsq/>ve arrived at a very clever algorithm for computing the PFD -->
    <!--       of a rational function of the form <m>\frac{c}{(x-a)(x-b)}</m> but -->
    <!--       we<rsq/>ll need to extend it several times if it is going to be more -->
    <!--       than minimally useful. The first extension is straightforward. -->
    <!--     </p> -->
    <!--   </introduction> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Show that the PFD of <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)}</m> can be -->
    <!--         computed in exactly the same manner as our most recent method -->
    <!--         for <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}</m>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--   </task> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Show the same for -->
    <!--         <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)(x-d)}</m>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--   </task> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Show the same for -->
    <!--         <m>\frac{1}{(x-x_1)(x-x_2)(x-x_3)\cdots(x-x_n)}</m>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--   </task> -->
    <!-- </exercise> -->



    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   As you can see from <xref ref="PROBLEMPFDSimplestForm"></xref> -->
    <!--   even in its simplest form the PFD can become a very large -->
    <!--   problem. For example suppose <m>n=100</m>. In that case -->
    <!--   we<rsq/>d need to find <m>100</m> coefficients. We <rsq/>d really -->
    <!--   like to make the method as efficient as possible. To that end -->
    <!--   there is one more refinement we<rsq/>ll need before moving on to -->
    <!--   more general problems. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <p>
      The most direct way to find <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is to add the
      fractions on the right-hand side of <xref
      ref="EQUATIONPFDDegrees">equation</xref>.


      
      <me>\frac{0x+1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{A\left(x-b\right)+B\left(x-a\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{\left(A+B\right)x+\left(-Ab-Ba\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}</me> 
    </p>
    <p>
      Comparing coefficients leads to the system of two equations in the two unknowns <m>A,\ B</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>A+B\amp{}=0</mrow> 
        <mrow> -Ab-Ba\amp{}=1 </mrow>
      </md> 
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPartFrac2x2">
      <p>
        Solve these two equations for <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> to show that
        <m>A=\frac{1}{a-b}</m> and <m>B=\frac{1}{b-a}</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      This was very straightforward and not too tedious, but what if
      we tried to do the same with three distinct factors
        
      <men
          xml:id="EQUATIONPFDThreeFactors">\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}+\frac{C}{x-c}</men>. 

      For now we are simply assuming that a PFD works for three or
        more linear factors.  But this true and  will follow from <xref
        ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref>, below.
    </p>

      <p>
        Adding the terms on the right we see that 
      </p>

      <p>

        <md>
          <mrow>\amp{}\frac{0x^2+0x+1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}</mrow>
          <mrow>
          \amp{}=\frac{A\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)+B\left(x-a\right)\left(x-c\right)+C\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}=\frac{\left(A+B+C\right)x^2-\left(A\left(b+c\right)+B\left(a+c\right)+C\left(a+b\right)\right)x+\left(Abc+Bac+Cab\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}</mrow> 
        </md>
        and equating corresponding coefficients from either side leads
        to the following system of three linear equations in the three
        unknowns <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.

        <md>
          <mrow>A+B+C\amp{}=0</mrow>
          <mrow>
            \left(b+c\right)A+\left(a+c\right)B+C\left(a+b\right)\amp{}=0
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            (bc)A+(ac)B+(ab)C\amp{}=1
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        This is certainly doable, but it is also very tedious.  Could you imagine
        if we had four factors? Or five? This  method is simple to
        understand and it will always work, but the amount of computation
        escalates   quickly as the number of linear factors
        increases. For this reason we (the authors) think of this as
        the <term>brute force</term> method. We<rsq/>d really prefer
        something a little easier to implement.
      </p>

      <p>
        To find a way to  simplify things a bit we<rsq/>ll look again
        at <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDDegrees">equation</xref>. We can clear the fractions  by 
        multipling both sides  by <m>(x-a)(x-b)</m>

        <!-- <me>\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{A\left(x-b\right)+B\left(x-a\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}</me>  -->

        <!-- it was the numerators that mattered at this point.  Thus, we -->
        <!-- must have -->
      which gives
      <me>1=A\left(x-b\right)+B\left(x-a\right)</me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <idx><h>Definition</h><h>identity</h></idx>
        Instead of expanding as we did before,
        notice that this equation is an <term>identity</term> which 
        means that it is true regardless of the value of 
        <m>x</m>.  Thus if we let
        <m>x=a</m> we get <m>1=A\left(a-b\right)+B(a-a)</m>
        or <m>A=\frac{1}{a-b}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>

        
      </p>
      <exercise>
        <p>
          What value of <m>x</m> should you choose for <m>x</m> in order
          to determine
          <m>B</m> with as little work as possible? Use your answer to
          find <m>B</m> and compare with your
          results in <xref ref="PROBLEMPartFrac2x2"></xref>.
        </p>
      </exercise>

      <problem xml:id="DRILLPFDWithoutCoverup">

        <p>
          Compute each integral by decomposing the integrand  using any of the methods you<rsq/>ve seen so far.
          <ol cols="2" marker="(i)">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\int\frac{1}{(x-2)(x-1)}\dx{x}</m>   
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\int \frac{1} {x(x-100 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\int \frac{4}{(x+2 )(x-2 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\int \frac{6}{(x-3 )(x+10 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\int \frac{\frac{2}{10}}{(x-10 )(x-100 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\int  \frac{1}{(2x- 5)(3x- 1)}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>

        </p>
      </problem>
      <exercise>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Compute each integral by decomposing the integrand  using any of the methods you<rsq/>ve seen so far.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x^2-9}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x^2-4}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{x^2-13x+36 }\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m> \displaystyle
              \int        \frac{1}{x^4-13x^2+36 }\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              Let <m>y=x^2</m> and use the results of parts (a), (b), and (c).
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
      </exercise>


      

      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPFDThreeDistinctFactors">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Does the process  change  when we have  three distinct
            linear factors?
          </p>
          <p>
            Certainly the first step is the same. Clearing the
            fraction in <xref
            ref="EQUATIONPFDThreeFactors">equation</xref> we have 

            <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDThreeClear">
              1=A\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)+B\left(x-a\right)\left(x-c\right)+C(x-a)(x-b)
            </men> 



          </p>

        </introduction>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Choose the appropriate value of <m>x</m> to determine
      to determine that

      <md>
        <mrow>
          A\amp{}=\frac{1}{\left(a-b\right)\left(a-c\right)}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          B\amp{}=\frac{1}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b-c\right)}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          C \amp{}=\frac{1}{\left(c-a\right)\left(c-b\right)}
        </mrow> 
      </md>


      Again, you should be able to do this with minimal
      calculation.


    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the result of part (a) to compute
      <me>
        \int{\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}
        \dx{x}}
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute
      <me>\int\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)\left(x-d\right)}
      \dx{x}</me>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use this the result of part (c) to compute
      <me>
        \int\frac{1}{x^4-13x^2+36}\dx{x} 
        </me> 
        directly. 
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Ideally factoring <m>x^4-13x^2+36</m> will be the
      hardest part of this problem. 
    </p>
  </hint>

</task>

      </exercise>


      <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEExtendedLogistic">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            As we<rsq/>ve mentioned before, all mathematical models make
            simplifying assumptions. It is important to know what are
            the simplifications are so we know the conditions under
            which the model is unrealistic. For example, <xref
            ref="EQUATIONFishery1">IVP</xref> works fine in the short
            term but in the long term it predicts explosive growth which
            is not sustainable. We addressed this when we generated the
            <xref ref="EQUATIONLogEq">Logistic Equation</xref> by
            including as a factor, <m>\left(
            1-\frac{P}{100}\right)</m>. That modification put an upper
            bound on the population size as we have seen.
          </p>

          <p>
            However the Logistic Equation doesn<rsq/>t put any lower bound on
            the population size. This is also unrealistic since we know that
            if a population of critters is too small they tend to die
            out. The following tweak to the logistic model: 
            <men xml:id="EQUATIONLogEqMinViable">
              \dfdx{P}{t}=0.1P\left(1-\frac{P}{100}\right)\left(1-\frac{10}{P}\right),
            </men>

            forces a population which is too small to die out.  In
            this case, <m>10</m> is called the <term>minimum viability
            level</term> of the population. Notice that the term <m>
            \left( 1-\frac{10}{P} \right)</m> is negative when <m>P
            \lt 10</m>, causing the population to shrink in size, but
            is close to <m>1</m> when <m>P</m> is relatively large so
            it is close to logistic growth for large populations.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the PFD of 
              <me>\frac{1}{(P-100)(P-10)}</me> and verify that
              your decomposition is correct. 
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the result of part (a) to show that 
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \dfdx{P}{t} \amp{}= 0.1P\left(1-\frac{P}{100}\right)\left(
                  1-\frac{10}{P}\right)
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp{}= -0.001(P-100)(P-10)
                </mrow>
              </md>
              is satisfied by 
              <me>P(t)= \frac{100-10Ke^{-0.09t}}{1-Ke^{-0.09t}}</me>
              where <m>K</m> is an arbitrary constant.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that if <m>P(0)=5</m>, then <m>K=19</m> and plot this curve. Is this consistent with calling <m>10</m> the <term>minimum
              viability level</term>?
              <!-- Use the graphical techniques -->
              <!-- of <xref ref="SECTIONExponentialGrowth"></xref> to sketch a qualitative graph of the solution of <xref -->
              <!-- ref="EQUATIONLogEqMinViable">equation</xref>.  -->
            </p>
            <!-- <p> -->
            <!--   Does the curve you get resemble the graph of <m>P(t)</m>? -->
            <!-- </p> -->

            <!-- <p> -->
            <!--   Explain -->
            <!--   what happens if our population drops below the <term>minimum -->
            <!--   viability level</term> -->

            <!-- </p> -->
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exercise>

      <p>
        We<rsq/>ve already simplified the PFD  process quite a bit,
        but in fact it can be (and will need to be)
        streamlined even further.
      </p>
      <p>
        When he was computing some PFDs related to his work with 
        differential equations
        <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Heaviside/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Heaviside/">Oliver Heaviside</url>
        (1850<mdash/>1925) made the following observation. Look closely at
        the numerators of the fractions the right side of
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDFirst">
          \frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}=
          \frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{b-a}}{x-b}
        </men> 
        Do you see that the numerator above <m>x-a</m> is what we
        would get if we simply replaced <m>x</m> with <m>a</m> on the
        left and <q>covered up,</q> (or ignored, or set equal to one)
        the factor <m>x-a</m>?
      </p>
        <p>
          That is, if <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}=
          \frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}</m> then 
          
          <me>A=\eval{\frac{1}{(\text{covered})(x-b)}}{x}{a}=\frac{1}{a-b}
          </me>.
          Similarly
          <me>B=\eval{\frac{1}{(x-a)(\text{covered})}}{x}{b}=\frac{1}{b-a}
          </me>.
          <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover<ndash/>up Method</h></idx>
          <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>HCUM</h></idx>
          This is known as <term>Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover<ndash/>up
          Method (HCUM)</term> and it is the simplest way we know to compute the
          coefficients of the PFD of the rational functions we<rsq/>ve seen so
          far.
        </p>

        <p>
          The HCUM is a very convenient shortcut. But it is necessary to
          understand why any  shortcut works. Otherwise all we have is the
          shortcut. If we encounter a problem where the shortcut won<rsq/>t
          work but the underlying principle will, and all we know is the
          shortcut we can<rsq/>t make any progress.
        </p>
        <p>
          To see why the HCUM works take another look at the decomposition 
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFD2LinFactors">
            \frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}
            </men>. 
            If we multiply both sides by <m>x-a</m>, we get 
          <me>\frac{1}{x-b}=A+\frac{B(x-a)}{x-b}</me> which holds as long as
          <m>x\ne b</m>. Notice that <m>\frac{1}{x-b} =
          \frac{1}{(\text{covered})(x-b)}</m>.
          Next,      if we take <m>x=a</m> we get
          <me>\frac{1}{a-b}=\frac{1}{(\text{covered})(a-b)}  =A+\frac{B(a-a)}{a-b}=A</me>.
        </p>
        <problem>
          <p>
            Use the method just outlined to show that if 
            <me>
            \frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}</me>
            then 
<me>B=\frac{1}{b-a}</me>
          </p>
        </problem>

        <exercise>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Based on our experience so far if we wanted to decompose
              the expression <m>\frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)}</m>
              we<rsq/>d try to find <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>
              in
              <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFD3Factors">
                \frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}+\frac{C}{x-c}</men>.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Multiply both sides of  <xref
                ref="EQUATIONPFD3Factors">equation</xref> by
                <m>(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)</m> and show that 
                <me>A= \frac{1}{(a-b)(a-c)}</me>. 
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                By a similar argument, show  that <m>B=\frac{1}{(b-a)(b-c)}</m>
                and <m>C=\frac{1}{(c-a)(c-b)}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <conclusion>
            <p>
              This problem shows that the HCUM also works when there
              are three linear factors in the denominator.  It is
              straightforward to generalize this result to an
              arbitrary number of linear factors.
            </p>
          </conclusion>

        </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <introduction>

            <p>
              Compute each integral by decomposing the integrand using using
              <term>Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover<ndash/>up Method</term> and confirm
              that your decomposition is correct.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{(x^2-4 )(x^2- 9)}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{(x-1 )(x-2 )(x-3 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{(x+1 )(x+2)(x+3 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{x(x^2-1)(x-3 )(x+8 )}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{(x-2 )(x+7 )(x-5 )(x+8)(x-3)}\dx{x}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
        </exercise>


        <!-- <exercise> -->
        <!--   <introduction> -->

        <!--     <p> -->
        <!--       To avoid obscuring our point, so far we<rsq/>ve kept the -->
        <!--       numerators and the coefficients of <m>x</m> simple. The -->
        <!--       numerators have always been some constant, usually <m>1</m>, -->
        <!--       and the coefficients of <m>x</m> have always been -->
        <!--       <m>1</m>. But this is not necessary.  -->
        <!--     </p> -->
        <!--     <p> -->
        <!--       Use Heaviside<rsq/>s -->
        <!--       method to compute each of the following integrals. Once you -->
        <!--       have the decomposition confirm that it is correct by adding -->
        <!--       your fractions together. -->
        <!--     </p> -->
        <!--   </introduction> -->
        <!--   <task> -->
        <!--     <statement> -->
        <!--       <p> -->
        <!--         <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{x}{(x^2-4 )(16x^2- 9)}\dx{x}</m> -->
        <!--       </p> -->
        <!--     </statement> -->
        <!--   </task> -->
        <!--   <task> -->
        <!--     <statement> -->
        <!--       <p> -->
        <!--         <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{x^2-1}{(3x-1 )(x-2 )(x-3 )}\dx{x}</m> -->
        <!--       </p> -->
        <!--     </statement> -->
        <!--   </task> -->
        <!--   <task> -->
        <!--     <statement> -->
        <!--       <p> -->
        <!--         <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{(x-1)(x-2)}{(2x+1 )(x+2)(3-x)}\dx{x}</m> -->
        <!--       </p> -->
        <!--     </statement> -->
        <!--   </task> -->
        <!--   <task> -->
        <!--     <statement> -->
        <!--       <p> -->
        <!--         <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{x^3}{x(x^2-1)(x-3)(5x+8)}\dx{x}</m> -->
        <!--       </p> -->
        <!--     </statement> -->
        <!--   </task> -->
        <!--   <task> -->
        <!--     <statement> -->
        <!--       <p> -->
        <!--         <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{x(x^3-1)}{(x-2 )(x+7 )(x-5 )(x+8)(x-3)}\dx{x}</m> -->
        <!--       </p> -->
        <!--     </statement> -->
        <!--   </task> -->
        <!-- </exercise> -->


      </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONPFDNonSimple">
    <title>Advanced Decompositions</title>

    <subsubsection>
      <title>Linear Factors</title>


      <example xml:id="EXAMPLEPFDUnreducedTwoMethods">   

        <p>
          Heaviside<rsq/>s method, as we have used it so far, will
          not work on the rational function
          <m>\frac{x^2}{(x-2)(x-3)}</m>.  If you try to apply it
          you<rsq/>ll get <me> \frac{x^2}{(x-2)(x-3)} =
          \frac{-4}{x-2}+\frac{9}{x-3}</me> which is wrong. Try it
          and see.
        </p>
        <p>
          The difficulty here is that, as a practical matter, the PFD
          requires that the degree of the numerator of our rational
          function to be strictly less than the degree of the
          denominator. (This is somewhat analogous to putting a
          fraction in <q>lowest terms.</q>) In this example the degree
          of the numerator is
          <me>
            \deg\left((x-2)(x-3)\right)=\deg\left(x^2-5x+6\right)=2
          </me>
          which is the same as the degree of the denominator: <m>
          \deg\left(x^2\right)=2</m>.  So the PFD, as we<rsq/>ve
          used it so far, doesn<rsq/>t
          apply.
        </p>
        <!-- <aside> -->
        <!--   <title>Comment</title> -->
        <!--   <p> -->
        <!--     To be clear this is a constraint we (the authors) are -->
        <!--     imposing for our (yours and our) convenience. The PFD -->
        <!--     can be computed without this constraint, but the method is more -->
        <!--     complex and does nothing to help us integrate rational functions -->
        <!--   </p> -->
        <!-- </aside> -->
        <p>
          At first this looks like it will be a major obstacle but it
          really isn<rsq/>t too bad. There are two ways we can
          proceed from here.
        </p>

        <p>
          <alert>Dividing First:</alert>
          The first is simply to do the polynomial division
          indicated. In practice that means 
          multiplying out the denominator first
          and then dividing: 
          <mdn>
            <mrow number="no">      
              \frac{x^2}{(x-2)(x-3)} =                  \frac{x^2}{x^2-5x+6} \amp{}= 1+ \frac{5x-6}{x^2-5x+6}
            </mrow>
            <mrow  xml:id="EQUATIONDividingFirst">
              \amp{}=1+\frac{5x-6}{(x-2)(x-3)}
            </mrow> 

          </mdn>

        </p>
        <p>
          From there we can compute the PFD of <m>
          \frac{5x-6}{(x-2)(x-3)}</m>
          as before, finally obtaining
          <me>\frac{x^2}{x^2-5x+6} = 1+\frac{-4}{x-2}+\frac{9}{x-3}
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          <alert>Dividing Last:</alert>
          The second is to factor out the numerator: 
          <me>\frac{x^2}{(x-2)(x-3)} = x^2
          \left[
          \frac{1}{(x-2)(x-3)}
          \right]                     </me>,
          compute the PFD of <m>\frac{1}{(x-2)(x-3)}</m>
          as before. This gives
          <mdn>
            <mrow number="no">
              \frac{x^2}{(x-2)(x-3)} \amp{}= x^2
              \left[
              \frac{-1}{x-2}+\frac{1}{x-3}
              \right]
            </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONDividingLast">
              \amp{}=\frac{-x^2}{x-2}+\frac{x^2}{x-3}
            </mrow>
            <mrow number="no">
              \amp{}=  -x-2-\frac{4}{x-2} +x+3+\frac{9}{x-3}
            </mrow>
            <mrow number="no">
              \amp{}=1-\frac{4}{x-2}+\frac{9}{x-3}.
            </mrow>
          </mdn>

        </p>


        <p>

          If you are uncomfortable with long division of polynomials,
          we can accomplish the same thing using a  substitution.  At
          the point where we 
          have
          
          <me>
          \frac{x^2}{\left(x-2\right)\left(x-3\right)}=-\frac{x^2}{x-2}+\frac{x^2}{x-3}
          </me> 

          if we let <m>y=x-2</m> in the first fraction and <m>z=x-3</m> in the second fraction, then we have
        </p>
          <p>


            <md>
              
              <mrow>\frac{x^2}{\left(x-2\right)\left(x-3\right)}\amp{}=-\frac{{\left(y+2\right)}^2}{y}+\frac{{\left(z+3\right)}^2}{z}</mrow> 
              <mrow>\amp{}=-\frac{y^2+4y+4}{y}+\frac{z^2+6z+9}{z}</mrow> 
              <mrow>\amp{}=-y-4-\frac{4}{y}+z+6+\frac{9}{z}</mrow> 
              <mrow>\amp{}=-x+2-4-\frac{4}{x-2}+x-3+6+\frac{9}{x-3}</mrow> 
              <mrow>\amp{}=1-\frac{4}{x-2}+\frac{9}{x-3}</mrow> 

            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Whether you divide first or divide last is entirely your
            choice, so choose whichever you are most comfortable with
            and use it.  But be flexible. Both 
            methods work. Use the one that feels more natural to you.
          </p>
      </example>
        
      <exercise>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Determine the PFD  by dividing first and by dividing
            last. When you divide last first use polynomial division,
            and then use the substitution to complete the
            decomposition. It should be the same in every case.
          </p>
          <p>
            Which do you prefer in each case?
          </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\frac{x^3}{\left(x-2\right)\left(x-3\right)}</m> 


              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\frac{x^4}{\left(x-2\right)\left(x-3\right)\left(x-1\right)}</m> 
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        
        There are two parts to computing the PFD of a rational
        function.   First we must determine the form of the
        decomposition and then we must  compute
        the unknown coefficients. From our discussion so far  we  know
        the form if the denominator is a product of distinct linear
        factors, 
        and we have a number of ways to compute the coefficients
        involved.  Being mathematicians, and therefore quite lazy,
        the authors<rsq/> inclination is to use the 
        more clever, less tedious approach whenever possible. 
      </p>
      <p>
        We can always resort to <term>brute force</term> computations as a last
        resort, but as the rational functions become more complicated,
        a little cleverness will save us a lot of computational
        effort.
      </p>

      <example xml:id="EXAMPLEFirstNonLinPartFrac">
        <p>
          Suppose we try the HCUM on <m>\frac{1}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</m>.
          If we do this without thinking, we will get
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>\frac{1}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=-\frac{1}{x^2}+\frac{1}{x-1}</me> 
        </p>
        <p>
          But this is incorrect as you can see.
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>-\frac{1}{x^2}+\frac{1}{x-1}=\frac{-x+1+x^2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</me> 
        </p>
        <p>
          Can you see what the problem is?  According to our Theorem, all
          we know is that the degrees of the numerators in our decomposition must be less
          than the degrees of the denominators.  This means our
          decompositions form should be
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONHeaviNonLinear1">\frac{1}{x^2(x-1)}=\frac{\left(Ax+B\right)}{x^2}+\frac{C}{x-1}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{x^2}+\frac{C}{x-1}</men>
        </p>
        <p>
          We can still use the HCUM to compute <m>B=-1,\ C=1.</m>
        </p>
      </example>


      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMFirstNonLinPartFrac">
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Explain why  the  HCUM can be used  to find  <m>B</m> and
              <m>C</m> in <xref ref="EQUATIONHeaviNonLinear1">equation</xref>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              It<rsq/>s the same reason it worked in <xref
              ref="EQUATIONPFDFirst">equation</xref>.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              You can solve <xref
              ref="EQUATIONHeaviNonLinear1">equation</xref> for
              <m>A</m> by setting <m>x</m> equal to (almost) any
              value we choose. Confirm this by showing  that if we set   <m>x=3</m>, <m>x=5</m>, or
              <m>x= 10</m>, we always get
              <m>A=-1</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              There are two values of <m>x</m> which will not allow
              us to compute <m>A</m>. What are they and why
              can<rsq/>t we use them? 
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Use 
            the result of the previous problem to find the PFD of:
          </p>

        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{2x-3}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>

              
              <m>\frac{x^2+x-3}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}\ </m>
            </p>
          </statement>

        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{x^4\left(x-1\right)}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <p>
          Let<rsq/>s re<ndash/>examine the PFD for
          <m>\frac{x^2-x+3}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</m> from part (b) in the
          last problem.  We could have directly noticed that the form of our
          PFD is

          <me>\frac{x^2-x+3}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{x^2}+\frac{C}{x-1}</me> 
        </p>
        <p>
          Use the HCUM directly on this to compute <m>B=-3</m>, and  <m>C=3</m>.  Employ
          any technique you wish to determine that <m>A=-2</m> and compare
          this to the answer you obtained in part (b) of the last problem.
        </p>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        As you have seen there are many ways to attack the PFD of a
        rational function.  The good news is that  you can use any algebraic
        technique to determine the coefficients.  Unfortunately that
        is also the bad news.
      </p>
      <p>
        In this section we (the authors) are building up a procedure
        for the PFD which is simple, both to understand and to
        implement, but it is not the only known procedure. And the PFD is not
        Calculus, it is Algebra. So for us it is simply a way to
        manipulate an integral into a form we can compute. So if you
        know, or can find, a better method for computing the PFD go
        ahead and use it.
      </p>
<p>

  Having so many options can make your head spin, especially if
  you are using techniques without fully  understanding why they
  work.  So think before you act and proceed deliberately.  With
  experience you will begin to see patterns and there will be
  fewer false starts.
</p>

<p>
  The theorem underlying all of this is <xref
  ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref> which we now state
  formally. 
</p>


<theorem xml:id="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp">
  <title>The Partial Fraction Decomposition (PFD)</title>
  <p>
    If <m>P(x)</m>, <m>Q(x)</m>, and <m>R(x)</m> are
    polynomials having no non<ndash/>trivial common factors with
    <m>\deg(P)\lt\deg(Q)+ \deg(R)</m> then there exist
    polynomials <m>A(x)</m> and <m>B(x)</m>, with 
    <m>\deg(A)\lt\deg(Q)</m> and <m>\deg(B)\lt\deg(R)</m>, such
    that <me>\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)\cdot{}R(x)} =
    \frac{A(x)}{Q(x)}+\frac{B(x)}{R(x)}</me>.
  </p>
</theorem>
<p>
  
  For example, suppose we had the rational function
</p>
<p>
  
  <me>\frac{x^2-x+2}{x{\left(x+1\right)}^2}</me> 
</p>
<p>


  By theorem 19.2.2.11, we know we can write this as

  
  <me>\frac{x^2-x+2}{x{\left(x+1\right)}^2}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{Bx+C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^2}</me> 


  but it is more convenient to write it as

  
  <me>\frac{x^2-x+2}{x{\left(x+1\right)}^2}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B(x+1)+C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^2}=\frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{x+1}+\frac{C}{{\left(x+1\right)}^2}</me> 
</p>



<exercise>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explain how we can use the HCUM to compute <m>A</m>
        and <m>C</m>
        and then show that <m>A=2</m> and <m>C=-4</m>.
      </p>

    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Substitute the values for <m>A</m>, and <m>C</m> into
        the PFD and compute <m>B</m> by any means you wish.
      </p>

    </statement>
  </task>


</exercise>


<exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPFDDistinctLinearFactors">

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Use the HCUM to
      compute the coefficients of the  PFD indicated.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>F</m>.

        <md>
          <mrow> \frac{1}{x^2(x-1)(x-3)^3}=\amp{} \frac{Ax+B}{x^2} + \frac{C}{x-1}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp{}+ 
            \frac{D(x-3)^2+E(x-3)+F}{(x-3)^3}
          </mrow>
        </md>
        Explain why the HCUM can not be used to find <m>A</m>,
        <m>D</m>, or <m>E</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>B</m> and <m>D</m>.
        <me>\displaystyle \frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2}=
        \frac{A(x-1)+B}{(x-1)^2}  +\frac{C(x+2)+D}{(x+2)^2} </me>
        Explain why the HCUM can not be used to find <m>A</m>,
        or <m>C</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>C</m>.
        <me>\frac{x-2}{(x+1)^3}=\frac{A}{x+1} + \frac{B}{(x+1)^2} +
        \frac{C}{(x+1)^3}</me>
        Explain why the HCUM can not be used to find <m>A</m>, or
        <m>B</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explain as clearly as you can from the evidence in parts (a),
        (b), and (c) which
        kinds of coefficients we can compute using the HCUM.
      </p>

    </statement>
  </task>


</exercise>
<p>
  In <xref ref="PROBLEMPFDDistinctLinearFactors"></xref> we only asked
  you to compute the coefficients that are obtainable using the
  HCUM. The other coefficients can be computed by any algebraic
  means you wish. Some are more onerous than others.  The next
  example shows  another way to compute them.
</p>

<example xml:id="EXAMPLEPFDRepeatedLinearFactors">
  <title>The PFD With Repeated Linear Factors</title>

  <p>
    Let<rsq/>s finish up the decomposition of 
    <m> \frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2}</m>
    from part (b) of <xref
    ref="PROBLEMPFDDistinctLinearFactors"></xref>. From the HCUM
    You should
    have found that <m>B=\frac19</m> and <m>D=\frac{-2}{9}</m> so that 
    <me>\displaystyle \frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2}= \frac{A}{x-1} +
    \frac{\frac19}{(x-1)^2} +\frac{C}{x+2}
    -\frac{\frac29}{(x+2)^2} </me>
    When we reached this point in <xref
    ref="EXAMPLEFirstNonLinPartFrac"></xref> (see part (b) of <xref
    ref="PROBLEMFirstNonLinPartFrac"></xref>) our next step was to  simply choose a value
    for <m>x</m>. We could do that here as well but because we now
    have two unknowns we<rsq/>d
    have to  choose two distinct values for
    <m>x</m> and   generate a system of two  coupled equations to
    solve.   We<rsq/>ve already seen that there are more efficient
    methods for computing the PFD than solving a system   of
    equations.
  </p>
  <p>
    Instead we<rsq/>ll isolate all of the terms with
    our unknowns on one side of the equation, thus:
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDDistLin1">\displaystyle \frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2} -
    \frac{\frac19}{(x-1)^2} +\frac{\frac29}{(x+2)^2} =          \frac{A}{x-1}  +\frac{C}{x+2}
    </men>
  </p>
  <p>
    It is clear that  the right side of <xref
    ref="EQUATIONPFDDistLin1">equation</xref> is the PFD of some rational function whose
    denominator is <m>(x-1)(x+2)</m>. That is, if we were asked
    to  begin the process of computing the PFD of
    <me>\frac{P(x)}{(x-1)(x+2)}</me> for some polynomial
    <m>P(x)</m> then our first step would be to write down the   right side of
    <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDDistLin1">equation</xref>. 
    Therefore it must be that 
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDDistLin2">\displaystyle \frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2} -
    \frac{\frac19}{(x-1)^2} +\frac{\frac29}{(x+2)^2} =  \frac{P(x)}{(x-1)(x+2)}
    </men>
    for some polynomial <m>P(x)</m>, and if we can find
    that polynomial we can compute <m>A</m> and <m>C</m> by the
    HCUM.
  </p>
  <p>
    To find  <m>P(x)</m>, we first clear the
    fraction on the right leaving,
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDDistinctLin2">
      \frac{x}{(x-1)(x+2)} -
      \frac19
      \left(
      \frac{x+2}{x-1}
      \right)
      +\frac29
      \left(
      \frac{x-1}{x+2}
      \right) =  P(x)
    </men>
    It is tempting to find a common denominator and add
    the three fractions on the left together. Since we have to end up
    with the polynomial <m>P(x)</m> it must be that once the addition
    is done there will be a factor in the top that will cancel with
    the common denominator.
  </p>
  <p>
    That will work. Give it a try if you want. Good luck. 
  </p>
  <p>
    But we know that <m>P(x)</m> is a polynomial and we can make very
    effective use of that knowledge as follows.
  </p>
  <p>
    If we perform this division in the second term on the left we get
    <me>\frac{x+2}{x-1} = 1 +\frac{3}{x-1}</me>. Similarly if we
    perform the division in the third term we get <m>\frac{x-1}{x+2}=
    1-\frac{3}{x+2}</m>. Putting these back into <xref
    ref="EQUATIONPFDDistinctLin2">equation</xref> we have
    <me>
      \frac{x}{(x-1)(x+2)} -
      \frac19
      \left(
      1 +\frac{3}{x-1}
      \right)
      +\frac29
      \left(
      1-\frac{3}{x+2}
      \right) =  P(x)
    </me>
    or
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDNumLessDen">
      \underbrace{\left(      \frac{x}{(x-1)(x+2)}  -\frac{\frac13}{x-1}
      -\frac{\frac23}{x+2}\right)}_{=0} + \frac19 = P(x) 
      </men>. 
      Since <m>P(x)</m> must be a
      polynomial it follows that the expression in the parentheses
      <mdash/> everything that is not a polynomial <mdash/>
      must be equal to zero, as we<rsq/>ve indicated above. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Thus
    <m>P(x)=\frac19{}</m>. 
    
    To finish the decomposition we place this in to <xref
    ref="EQUATIONPFDDistLin2">equation</xref> and observe that 
    <me>\frac{\frac19 }{(x-1)(x+2)} =
    \frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{C}{x+2}</me> 
    and from the HCUM we see that <m>A=\frac{1}{27}        </m>
    and <m>C=-\frac{1}{27}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Having found all of the constants we conclude from <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDDistLin1">equation</xref> that
    <me>\frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2}= \frac{\frac{1}{27}}{x-1} +
    \frac{\frac19 }{(x-1)^2} -\frac{\frac{1}{27}}{x+2} -\frac{\frac29
    }{(x+2)^2} 
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Naturally, it isn<rsq/>t always that simple. If the degree of
    any (or all) of the numerators in <xref
    ref="EQUATIONPFDNumLessDen">equation</xref> was not less than
    it<rsq/>s denominator then we<rsq/>d have had to compute the
    division in order to recover the polynomial part of each. But
    then the sum of the remainders would necessarily be zero so they
    can be ignored just as we ignored <m> \frac{x}{(x-1)(x+2)}
    -\frac{\frac13}{x-1} -\frac{\frac23}{x+2}</m> above.
  </p>
</example> 

<problem>
  <p>
    Confirm that the decomposition in <xref
    ref="EXAMPLEPFDRepeatedLinearFactors"></xref> is correct.
  </p>


  
</problem>



<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONReducedRatFunc">
  <title>Reduced Rational Functions </title>
  <idx><h>Definition</h><h>reduced rational function</h></idx>

  <statement>
    <p>
      We will call a rational function where the degree of the
      numerator is less than the degree of the denominator a
      <term>reduced rational function.</term>
    </p>

  </statement>
</definition>

<exercise>
  <p>

    In <xref ref="EXAMPLEPFDRepeatedLinearFactors"></xref> we stated
    without justification that the sum of the <term>reduced rational
    functions</term> <m>\frac{x}{(x-1)(x+2)}  -\frac{\frac13}{x-1}
    -\frac{\frac23}{x+2}</m> would be another <term>reduced rational
    function</term> but is that really true? This problem
    explores that question.
  </p>



  <p>
    Suppose  that
    <m>\frac{A(x)}{B(x)}</m> and  <m>\frac{C(x)}{D(x)}</m>, are
    <term>reduced rational functions.</term>
    Show that the sum
    <me>\frac{A(x)}{B(x)}+\frac{C(x)}{D(x)}= \frac{A(x)\cdot
    D(x)+C(x)\cdot B(x)}{B(x)\cdot D(x)}</me> 
    is also a <term>reduced rational function</term>.
  </p>


  
  
</exercise>

<exercise>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Of course, we<rsq/>re not just computing the PFDs for
      fun. For us the Partial Fraction Decomposition is a tool
      which will enable us compute integrals we can<rsq/>t
      compute by other means. Notice that we cannot compute any
      of the integrals in this problem without first  using the
      PFD to change the integrand into something more manageable.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <!-- <task> -->
  <!--   <statement> -->
  <!--     <p> -->
  <!--       Use the results of <xref -->
  <!--       ref="EXAMPLEPFDRepeatedLinearFactors"></xref> to compute <me>\int -->
  <!--       \frac{x}{(x-1)^2(x+2)^2}\dx{x}</me>. -->
  <!--     </p> -->
  <!--   </statement> -->
  <!-- </task> -->
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Combine your results from part (a) of <xref
        ref="PROBLEMPFDDistinctLinearFactors"></xref> and what you
        learned from <xref ref="EXAMPLEPFDRepeatedLinearFactors"></xref>  to compute
        <me> \int \frac{1}{x^2(x-1)(x-3)^3}\dx{x}</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Combine your results from part (c) of <xref
        ref="PROBLEMPFDDistinctLinearFactors"></xref> and what you
        learned from <xref ref="EXAMPLEPFDRepeatedLinearFactors"></xref>  to compute
        <me>\int\frac{x-2}{(x+1)^3}\dx{x}</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>

</exercise>
<exercise>
  <task>
    <statement>

      <p>
        Apply <xref ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref>
        three times to show that the following PFD is valid

        
        <me>\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}+\frac{C}{x-c}</me> 


        where <m>a,b,c\ </m>are distinct numbers

      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use <xref ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref> to show
        that the following PFD is also valid

        <me>\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)\left(x-d\right)}=\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b}+\frac{C}{x-c}+\frac{D}{x-d}\ </me> 
        where <m>a,b,c,d</m> are distinct numbers.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
</exercise>
</subsubsection>


<subsubsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONPFDIrreducQuadFac">
  <title>Irreducible Quadratic Factors</title>
  <p>
    So far whenever there was a quadratic factor in the
    denominator we were able to either factor it into two distinct
    linear factors (e.g. <m>(x^2-x+6) = (x+2)(x-3)</m> or into one
    such factor, squared, e.g.  <m>(x^2+6x+9)=(x+3)^2</m>.
    Unfortunately we cannot yet compute the integral <me>\int
    \frac{1}{(x-2)(x^2+1)}\dx{x}</me>, because the factor
    <m>x^2+1</m> cannot be factored (over the real numbers). So
    we<rsq/>ll need to extend our procedure to account for this situation.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Comment</title>
    <p>
      But it can be factored over the complex numbers. We will
      address this at the end of this section.
    </p>
  </aside>

  
  <p>
    From our previous work we know that 
    <me>\frac{1}{(x-2)(x^2+1)}=
    \frac{A}{x-2}+\frac{Bx+C}{x^2+1}</me> 
    so by the HCUM <m>A=\frac15 </m>.

    Therefore
    <me>\frac{1}{(x-2)(x^2+1)}=
    \frac{\frac15}{x-2}+ \frac{Bx+C}{x^2+1}</me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    As we keep repeating this is an identity; it is true
    regardless of the value of <m>x</m> .  If we
    isolate the expression <m>Bx+C</m> on the right side of the
    equation then the left side will reduce to a linear
    expression in <m>x</m>. We can then simply compare the
    coefficients.  
  </p>
  <p>
    Multiplying both sides by <m>x^2+1</m> we have 
    <me>\frac{1}{x-2}=\frac15 \left(\frac{x^2+1}{x-2}\right)+(Bx+C)
    </me>
    and isolating <m>Bx+C</m> gives
    <me>\frac{1}{x-2}-\frac15\left( \frac{x^2+1}{x-2}\right)=Bx+C
    </me>,
    and  simplifying the expression on the left we see
    that 
    <me>Bx+C=-\frac15x -\frac25 </me>, so 
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONFirstPFDExample">\frac{1}{(x-2)(x^2+1)}=
    \frac{\frac15}{x-2}-
    \frac{\frac15x}{x^2+1} -\frac{\frac25}{x^2+1}</men>.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMIrredQuadPartFrac">
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Confirm that <xref
          ref="EQUATIONFirstPFDExample">equation</xref> is
          correct by getting a common denominator and adding the
          terms on the right together.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the integral <m>\displaystyle
          \int\frac{1}{x(x^2+1)}\dx{x} </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the integral <m>\displaystyle
          \int\frac{1}{(x-2)^2(x^2+3)}\dx{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the integral <m>\displaystyle
          \int\frac{1}{(x^2+5)^2(x^2+4)}\dx{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task> 
  </exercise>
  <p>
    Reasoning by analogy it seems reasonable to speculate that
    the PFD of <m>\frac{1}{x^2(x^2+1)^3(x^2+9)(x-5)}    </m> will be 

    <mdn>
      <mrow
          xml:id="EQUATIONBigPFD">\frac{1}{x^2(x^2+1)^3(x^2+9)(x-5))}
      =
      \frac{A}{x}+\frac{B}{x^2}+\amp{}\frac{Cx+D}{x^2+1}+\frac{Ex+F}{(x^2+1)^2}</mrow>
      <mrow number="no">
        +\frac{Gx+H}{(x^2+1)^3}
      \amp{}+ \frac{Ix+J}{x^2+9}+\frac{K}{x-5},</mrow>
    </mdn>
    and that is correct.  <xref
    ref="EQUATIONBigPFD">Equation</xref> is an example of the
    most general form that a Partial Fraction Decomposition can
    have. Beyond that they just get bigger.
    The good news is that we are done. 
  </p>
  <p>
    The really good news is that we won<rsq/>t be asking you to
    compute this decomposition.  On the other hand, if you would
    like to challenge your understanding try computing this
    decomposition  using the methods we<rsq/>ve discussed. Do it
    some time when you have an afternoon and evening free. It
    will take a while.
  </p>
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   The HCUM can still be used to compute <m>B</m> and <m>K</m> -->
  <!--   immediately.  It can even be extended to compute <m>G</m>, -->
  <!--   <m>H</m>, <m>I</m> and <m>J</m> fairly quickly.  But it -->
  <!--   would take us more time and effort to develop and discuss -->
  <!--   the extension than it is worth because we will not be -->
  <!--   encountering any decompositions this complicated. So we will -->
  <!--   stop here. -->
  <!-- </p> -->



  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   You can see why we did not begin this section by stating -->
  <!--   <xref -->
  <!--       ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref>. The language is so terse that it is actually -->
  <!--   hard to recognize this theorem as describing everything we -->
  <!--   have been through in this section. Nevertheless,  covers every kind -->
  <!--   of decomposition we have looked at so far. -->
  <!-- </p> -->
</subsubsection>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="SUBSUBSECTIONAvoidIrredCase">
  <title>Avoiding the Irreducible Case by Allowing Complex Numbers</title>
  <!--   <p> -->

  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </subsubsection> -->
  <!-- <paragraphs xml:id="DIGRESSIONComplexPFD"> -->
  <!--   <title>DIGRESSION:  -->
  <!--   Numbers</title> -->
  <p>
    Traditionally a course in Calculus studiously avoids using
    complex and imaginary numbers for reasons that have always
    eluded the authors. As we saw in <xref
    ref="SECTIONEulerHarmonicOsc"></xref> there are times when using
    the complex numbers can considerably simplify the problem. This
    is another such situation.
  </p>

  <p>
    The theorem that every polynomial can be completely factored
    into (possibly repeated) linear factors is known by the rather
    pompous name <term>The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra</term>. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Since this is in fact a  theorem (meaning that it has been
    proved)  an obvious question presents itself:
    <q>Why did we bother with the Irreducible Quadratic case when
    discussing the Partial Fraction Decomposition?</q> That is, why
    did we (the authors) tell you that <m>x^2+1</m> can<rsq/>t be
    factored, when the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra says that it can?
  </p>
  <p>
    Recall that in the first paragraph of the subsection <xref
    ref="SUBSECTIONPFDIrreducQuadFac" text="custom">Irreducible
    Quadratic Factors</xref> we were careful to state that
    <q><m>x^2+1</m></q> cannot be factored over the <term>real
    numbers</term>. This is true but it can be factored over the
    <term>complex numbers</term> (real numbers plus imaginary
    numbers).
    <url
        href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Gauss/"
        visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Gauss/">
      C. F. Gauss</url> (1777<ndash/>1855) attempted to prove the
      Fundamental Theorem of Algebra
      four times. His first attempt was  in
      his PhD dissertation, but that proof wasn<rsq/>t complete.
  </p>
  <p>
    Dissatisfied with his first effort he tried three more times
    over the course of his life, with better results. His last
    proof was published fully fifty years after his first and relied
    heavily on the complex numbers
  </p>
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   While Gauss<rsq/>s proof didn<rsq/>t make explicit use -->
  <!--   of  <term>complex -->
  <!--   numbers</term> they were implicit in his approach and -->
  <!--   his proof was valid. This was -->
  <!--   quite a puzzle at the time because while his proof said that -->
  <!--   <m>x^2+1</m> could be factored,  the nature of the -->
  <!--   factors was not clear.  When Gauss proved the -->
  <!--   Fundamental Theorem of Algebra the <term>complex -->
  <!--   numbers</term> were not well understood at all and had -->
  <!--   not been accepted. --> 
  <p>
    The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra
    is one of the results that forced mathematicians to
    undertake the study of the  <term>complex
    numbers</term> and eventually accept them as an extension of the
    real numbers.
  </p>
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   If it can be factored into say <m>x^2+1=(x-a)(x=b)</m> -->
  <!--   then we didn<rsq/>t need the Irreducible Quadratic case at -->
  <!--   all. The decomposition of <m>\frac{1}{x^2+1}</m> is just -->


  <!--   <md> -->
  <!--     <mrow> -->
  <!--       \frac{1}{x^2+1}= -->
  <!--       \frac{1}{(x-a)(x-b)}\amp{}=\frac{\eval{\frac{1}{(\text{covered})(x-b)}}{x}{a}}{x-a} -->
  <!--       +\frac{\eval{\frac{1}{(x-a)(\text{covered})}}{x}{b}}{1-b}  -->
  <!--     </mrow> -->
  <!--     <mrow> -->
  <!--       \amp{}=\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{b-a}}{x-b}, -->
  <!--     </mrow> -->
  <!--   </md> -->
  <!--   and we can compute the integral from there. Why is the -->
  <!--   Irreducible Quadratic case needed. -->
  <!-- </p> -->

  <!-- <aside> -->
  <!--   <title>Historical Context</title> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     While Gauss<rsq/>s proof didn<rsq/>t make explicit use -->
  <!--     of  <term>complex -->
  <!--     numbers</term> they were implicit in his approach. Moreover, -->
  <!--     his proof was generally recognized as valid. This was -->
  <!--     quite a puzzle at the time because his proof said that -->
  <!--     <m>x^2+1</m> could be factored, but the nature of the -->
  <!--     factors was not clear because when Gauss proved the -->
  <!--     Fundamental Theorem of Algebra the <term>complex -->
  <!--     numbers</term> were not well understood at all and had -->
  <!--     not been accepted.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra -->
  <!--     is one of the results that forced mathematicians to -->
  <!--     undertake the study of the  <term>complex -->
  <!--     numbers</term>. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </aside> -->

  <exercise>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>i=\sqrt{-1}</m> as in <xref
          ref="SECTIONEulerHarmonicOsc"></xref>  and show that
          <me>x^2+1 = (x-i)(x+i)</me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the result of part (a) to show that
          <me>\int \frac{1}{x^2+1}\dx{x} = \frac{i}{2}\ln
          \left(
          \frac{x+i}{x-i}
          \right)   +C
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Recall that we<rsq/>ve already seen that <m>\int
          \frac{1}{x^2+1}\dx{x} = \inverse \tan(x) +C</m>. In
          view of the result in part (b), do you believe
          that
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONLnArctan">\frac{i}{2}\ln
          \left(
          \frac{x+i}{x-i}
          \right)   +C = \inverse \tan(x) +C
          </men>?
        </p>
        <p>
          Notice that we have not asked if this is true,
          only if you believe it. Hence there is no right or
          wrong answer to the following question: Explain
          why you do or don<rsq/>t believe that <xref
          ref="EQUATIONLnArctan">equation</xref>. Give mathematical
          reasons to support your opinion either way.
        </p>

      </statement>
    </task>


  </exercise>

  <!-- <p> -->


  <!--   For suppose we want to decompose the rational function -->
  <!--   <m>\frac{x-2}{x(x^2+1)}</m>. According to Gauss<rsq/>s -->
  <!--   theorem There are no real numbers, <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, -->
  <!--   with the property that <m>x^2+1=(x-a)(x-b)</m> but -->
  <!--   <m>a=i</m> and <m>b=-i</m> (where as before <m>i^2=-1</m>) -->
  <!--   will work just fine since -->
  <!--   <me>(x-i)(x+i)=x^2-i^2=x^2-(-1)=x^2+1</me> -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   Unfortunately, Gauss<rsq/>s theorem  not true. For the Fundamental -->
  <!--   Theorem of Algebra to hold we need to allow the polynomial -->
  <!--   to have <term>complex</term> as apposed to <term>real</term> -->
  <!--   roots.  That is we need to expand our number system to -->
  <!--   include the <term>complex numbers <m>\CC </m></term> (a -->
  <!--   complex number is a real number plus an imaginary -->
  <!--   number). We first encountered the complex numbers in <xref -->
  <!--   ref="PROBLEMEulersFormula"></xref> in connection with -->
  <!--   <term>Euler<rsq/>s Identity</term>.  -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <example>
    <p>
      By allowing the use of <term>complex numbers</term> we
      can use the HCUM to compute

      <md>

        <mrow>\frac{x-2}{x(x^2+1)}=\frac{x-2}{x(x-i)(x+i)}
        \amp{}=\frac{-2}{x}+\frac{\frac{i-2}{i(2i)}}{x-i}+\frac{\frac{i+2}{i(-2i)}}{x+i}</mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=
          \frac{-2}{x}+\frac{\frac{i-2}{-2}}{x-i}+\frac{\frac{-i-2}{-2}}{x+i}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=\frac{-2}{x}+\frac{1-\frac12i}{x-i}+\frac{1+\frac12i
          }{x+i}.
        </mrow>

      </md>

    </p>
    <p>
      If <m>a+bi</m> is a complex number then <m>a-bi</m> is
      called its <term>conjugate</term>.  In general, the
      complex factors of a polynomial with real coefficients,
      if any exist, will always occur in conjugate pairs, so
      if a PFD is obtained by using complex numbers you can
      always hide the complex numbers by combining the terms
      with conjugate roots.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore, if for any reason  it is desired to remove the complex numbers
      from our decomposition we compute the sum
      <m>\frac{1-\frac12i}{x-i}+\frac{1+\frac12i }{x+i}</m> as
      follows
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDComplex1">
        \frac{1-\frac12i}{x-i}+\frac{1+\frac12i }{x+i}=\frac{2x+1}{x^2+1}
        </men>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus our decomposition over the real numbers (rather than the
      complex numbers is <men
      xml:id="EQUATIONPFDComplex2">\frac{x-2}{x(x^2+1)}=\frac{-2}{x}+\frac{2x+1}{x^2+1}</men>.
      Compare this with your solution to part (b) of <xref
      ref="PROBLEMIrredQuadPartFrac"></xref>.
    </p>

  </example>

  <!-- <exercise> -->
  <!--   <task> -->
  <!--     <statement> -->
  <!--       <p> -->
  <!--         Confirm that <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDComplex1">equation</xref> is -->
  <!--         correct. -->

  <!--       </p> -->
  <!--     </statement> -->
  <!--   </task> -->
  <!--   <task> -->
  <!--     <statement> -->
  <!--       <p> -->
  <!--         Confirm that <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDComplex2">equation</xref> is -->
  <!--         correct. -->
  <!--       </p> -->
  <!--     </statement> -->
  <!--   </task> -->
  <!-- </exercise> -->

  <!--   <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p> -->
  <!-- </paragraphs> -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title>DIGRESSION: How Did We Get a PFD</title>
    <p>
      Throughout this section we<rsq/>ve been citing <xref
      ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref> to justify the
      existence of a PFD for a rational function and we<rsq/>ve used a
      number of shortcuts to determine the coefficients involved.  It
      turns out that <xref ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref>  can be derived from long division of
      polynomials, but instead of doing that, we will take the
      opportunity to build a PFD from the ground up though some
      illustrative examples and exercises.  This could actually be
      used to compute the PFD of a given rational function in a
      systematic way but is not nearly as efficient as the methods
      employed.  We are really only using it here to justify that a
      PFD does in fact exist for a given rational function.  Some of
      what we have here will look familiar, but it will be included to
      give an entire picture of how a PFD is built starting with
      basics.
    </p>
    <p>
      To begin, notice that 
      <me>
      \frac{1}{x-a}-\frac{1}{x-b}=\frac{\left(x-b\right)-\left(x-a\right)}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{a-b}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}
      </me> 
      This says that if <m>a\neq b</m>, then

      <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDFoundation">
        \frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}
        =\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{x-a}-\frac{1}{x-b}\right)
      </men>
      or
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONPFDFoundation">
        \frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{b-a}}{x-b} 
      </men>

      which agrees with what we obtained in <xref
      ref="PROBLEMPartFrac2x2"></xref>. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Earlier, we also made the claim that we can find a PFD for three
      or more distinct linear factors, and that this follows from
      <xref ref="THEOREMPartialFractionDecomp"></xref>.  We can utilize <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDFoundation">formula</xref>  obtain this as
      well and we can use what we already did.  Suppose <m>a</m>,
      <m>b</m>, and 
      <m>c</m> are distinct real numbers.  Then

      <md>
        <mrow>
          \frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}\amp{}=\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{x-a}-\frac{1}{x-b}\right)\left(\frac{1}{x-c}\right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp{}=\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-c\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}\right)
          </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDFoundation">equation</xref> on
            the two fractions in the parentheses above to obtain the
            PFD
            <me>
            \frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{\frac{1}{\left(a-b\right)\left(a-c\right)}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b-c\right)}}{x-b}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(c-b\right)\left(c-a\right)}}{x-c}
            </me>
            which is what we obtained in <xref
            ref="PROBLEMPFDThreeDistinctFactors"></xref>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose we have four distinct real numbers <m>a,b,c,d</m>.
            Using the result obtained in part a, we obtain

            <md>
              <mrow>
                \amp{}\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)\left(x-d\right)}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                \amp{}=\left(\frac{\frac{1}{\left(a-b\right)\left(a-c\right)}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b-c\right)}}{x-b}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(c-b\right)\left(c-a\right)}}{x-c}\right)\left(\frac{1}{x-d}\right)
</mrow>
            </md>

            Use <xref ref="EQUATIONPFDFoundation">equation</xref> to
            show that we have the PFD

            <md>
              <mrow>
                \frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)\left(x-d\right)}=\amp{}
              </mrow>
<mrow>
  \amp{}\frac{\frac{1}{\left(a-b\right)\left(a-c\right)(a-d)}}{x-a}
</mrow>
<mrow>
\amp{}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b-c\right)\left(b-d\right)}}{x-b}
</mrow>
<mrow>
\amp{}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(c-a\right)\left(c-b\right)\left(c-d\right)}}{x-c}
</mrow>
<mrow>
  \amp{}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(a-b\right)\left(a-c\right)\left(d-a\right)}+\frac{1}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b-c\right)\left(d-b\right)}+\frac{1}{\left(c-a\right)\left(c-b\right)\left(d-c\right)}}{x-d}
</mrow>
            </md>

            Compare this result to what you get using the HCUM.  [You
            can see why we are using <xref
            ref="EQUATIONPFDFoundation">equation</xref> to show the
            existence of a PFD, instead of using it to determine the
            coefficients.]
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>   

    <p>
      So far, we<rsq/>ve looked at the existence of a PFD for a rational
      function whose numerator is one.  As we indicated in <xref
      ref="EXAMPLEPFDUnreducedTwoMethods"></xref>, the case where the
      numerator is not one can be handled by factoring it out and
      applying the appropriate substitutions.  We will utilize the
      following as an illustrative example, but it should be clear
      that this technique could be generalized.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Find the PFD of <m>\frac{2x^2+x+1}{\left(x-4\right)\left(x-2\right)}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that we can write this as

        <md>
          <mrow>
            \frac{2x^2+x+1}{\left(x-4\right)\left(x-2\right)}\amp{}=\left(2x^2+x+1\right)\left(\frac{1}{\left(x-4\right)\left(x-2\right)}\right)
          </mrow>
<mrow>
          \amp{}
          =\left(2x^2+x+1\right)\left(\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{x-4}-\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{x-2}\right)
          </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{}
              =\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{2x^2+x+1}{x-4}-\frac{2x^2+x+1}{x-2}\right)
            </mrow>
        </md>

        If we let <m>y=x-4</m> and <m>z=x-2</m>, we get

        <md>
          <mrow>
          \frac{2x^2+x+1}{\left(x-4\right)\left(x-2\right)}\amp{}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{2{\left(y+4\right)}^2+\left(y+4\right)+1}{y}-\frac{2{\left(z+2\right)}^2+\left(z+2\right)+1}{z}\right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
          \amp{}
          =\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{2y^2+17y+37}{y}-\frac{2z^2+9z+11}{z}\right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
          \amp{}
          =\frac{1}{2}\left(2y+17+\frac{37}{y}-2z-9-\frac{11}{z}\right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp{}=\frac{1}{2}\left(2y-2z+8+\frac{37}{y}-\frac{11}{z}\right)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
          \amp{}
          =y-z+4+\frac{\frac{37}{2}}{y}-\frac{\frac{11}{2}}{z}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
          \amp{}          =x-4-x+2+4+\frac{\frac{37}{2}}{x-4}-\frac{\frac{11}{2}}{x-2}
          </mrow>
<mrow>
\amp{}=2+\frac{\frac{37}{2}}{x-4}-\frac{\frac{11}{2}}{x-2}</mrow>

        </md>
            </p>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Apply the same technique to determine the PFD of
      <me>\frac{x^3}{\left(x-4\right)\left(x-2\right)}</me>
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    As we said, this technique can be generalized to any rational
    function whose denominator is a product of distinct linear
    factors.  It can also be used if there is a repeated linear
    factor.  Again, it suffices to do this where the numerator is one.
  </p>


  <example>
    <p>
      Let <m>a,b</m> be distinct real numbers.  Then

      <md>
        <mrow>
          \frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2\left(x-b\right)}\amp{}=\frac{1}{x-a}\left(\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}\right)
        </mrow> 
        <mrow>
        \amp{}
        =\frac{1}{x-a}\left(\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{x-a}-\frac{1}{x-b}\right)\right)
        </mrow> 
        <mrow>
        \amp{}
        =\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}-\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)}\right)
        </mrow> 
        <mrow>
        \amp{}
        =\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}-\frac{1}{a-b}\left(\frac{1}{x-a}-\frac{1}{x-b}\right)\right)
        </mrow> 
        <mrow>
        \amp{}
        =\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}-\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{x-b}
        </mrow> 
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Again, don<rsq/>t try to memorize such a formula.  The purpose of
      this is to show that such a PFD exists.  There are more
      efficient ways to compute the coefficients as you have seen.
    </p>
</example>
<exercise>  
  <p>
    Use the fact that 

    <md>
      <mrow>
        \frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^3\left(x-b\right)}\amp{}=\frac{1}{x-a}\left(\frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2\left(x-b\right)}\right)
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
        \amp{}=\frac{1}{x-a}\left(\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}-\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{x-b}\right)
      </mrow> 
    </md>
    to show that 
    <me>
    \frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^3\left(x-b\right)}=\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{{\left(x-a\right)}^3}-\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}+\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^3}}{x-a}-\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^3}}{x-b}
    </me> 
  </p>
  </exercise> 

  <p>
    Use the fact that

    <md>
      <mrow>
        \frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2{\left(x-b\right)}^2}\amp{}=\left(\frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2\left(x-b\right)}\right)\left(\frac{1}{x-b}\right)
        </mrow>
<mrow>
\amp{}=\left(\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}-\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{x-b}\right)\left(\frac{1}{x-b}\right)
      </mrow> 

    </md>
    to show that
    <me>\frac{1}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2{\left(x-b\right)}^2}=\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{{\left(x-a\right)}^2}-\frac{\frac{2}{{\left(a-b\right)}^3}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{2}{{\left(a-b\right)}^3}}{x-b}+\frac{\frac{1}{{\left(a-b\right)}^2}}{{\left(x-b\right)}^2}</me> 
  </p>
  <p>
    We<rsq/>ve taken care of the existence of a PFD where the denominator is a product of (possibly repeated) linear factors.  What about an irreducible quadratic factor?  As we saw before, if we utilize complex numbers, then these can be factored into linear factors as well.  The beauty is that in the end, we will have real numbers as our coefficients.  To see this, we need to look a little into complex number arithmetic.  Perhaps even more surprising is that all this hinges on the notion of a complex conjugate.  Given a complex number <m>z=a+bi</m>, its complex conjugate is given by <m>\bar{z}=a-bi</m>.  The following are facts about complex conjugates.
  </p>
  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMComplexConjugates">
    <title>Properties of the Complex Conjugate </title>
    <p>
      Let <m>z=a+bi</m> and <m>w=c+di</m>, then

      <ol cols="2" marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\overline{z+w}=\bar{z}+\bar{w}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\overline{z\cdot w}=\bar{z}\cdot
            \bar{w}</m> 
          </p> 
        </li> 
        <li> 
          <p> 
            <m>z+\bar{z}=2a</m> which is a real number 
          </p>
        </li> 
        <li> 
          <p> 
            <m>z-\bar{z}=2bi</m>
          </p> 
        </li> 
        <li> 
          <p>
            <m>z\cdot \bar{z}=a^2+b^2</m> which is a
            nonnegative real number.  
          </p> 
        </li> 
      </ol>
    </p>
    </theorem> 
    <exercise> 
      <p> 
        Prove <xref ref="THEOREMComplexConjugates"></xref>.  
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <p> 
      As was said previously, the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra says
      that every nonconstant polynomial with real coefficients has at
      least one root which could be a complex number.  A consequence
      of this is that any nonconstant polynomial and be factored
      entirely into linear factors where some of the factors may
    involve complex roots. 
    </p>
    <p> 
      Specifically, if 
      <me>
        p\left(x\right)=a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2+\dots +a_nx^n 
        </me> 
        is a
        real polynomial with roots <m>r_1, r_2, \dots, r_n</m>,
    (some roots possibly repeated, some possibly complex), then
    <me>
      p\left(x\right)=a_n\left(x-r_1\right)\left(x-r_2\right)\dots
      (x-r_n)
      </me>.
      The interesting thing about
      <m>p\left(x\right)</m> is that if it has a root which is a
      complex number <m>z</m> then <m>\bar{z}</m>is
      also a root.  
    </p> 

    <exercise>          

      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that if <m>z</m> is a root of  
          <me>
            p\left(x\right)=a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2+\dots +a_nx^n
            </me>, then <m>\bar{z}</m> is also a root.
        </p>

      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>

          If z is a root, then <m>a_0+a_1z+a_2z^2+\dots +a_nz^n=0</m>.
          Take the conjugate of this and use properties in <xref
          ref="THEOREMComplexConjugates"></xref>.  Also note that any
          real number is its own conjugate.
        </p>

      </hint>
    </exercise>  
    <p>
      The first consequence of this is that any real polynomial which
      is irreducible must be of degree 1 or 2. To see this, suppose we
      have a real polynomial <m>p(x)</m> of degree greater than 2.  If
      one of the roots of this polynomial is real, say <m>r</m>, then
      we can write <m>p\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)q(x)</m> for
      some polynomial <m>q(x)</m> whose degree is at least two.  This
      says <m>p\left(x\right)\ </m>is not irreducible.  If <m>p(x)</m>
      has a complex root <m>z</m>, then <m>\bar{z}\ </m>is
      also a root, and we can write
      <m>p\left(x\right)=\left(x-z\right)\left(x-\bar{z}\right)q(x)</m> where <m>q\left(x\right)\ </m>has degree at
      least one.
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        Multiply <m>\left(x-z\right)\left(x-\bar{z}\right)</m> and
        conclude that it is a polynomial with real coefficients.  This
        says that <m>p\left(x\right)</m> is not irreducible.
      </p>
      </exercise>    

      <p>
        With these preliminaries established, suppose we have the
        rational function
        <me>\frac{1}{\left(x^2+ax+b\right)\left(x-c\right)}</me> where
        <m>x^2+ax+b</m> is an irreducible real polynomial and <m>c</m>
        is a real number.  If we factor <m>x^2+ax+b</m> over the
        complex numbers, we get
        <me>\frac{1}{\left(x^2+ax+b\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{1}{\left(x-z\right)\left(x-\bar{z}\right)\left(x-c\right)}</me>
      </p>
    <p>


      Note that everything we<rsq/>ve done so far works over the complex numbers, so utilizing
      <me>\frac{1}{\left(x-a\right)\left(x-b\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{\frac{1}{\left(a-b\right)\left(a-c\right)}}{x-a}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b-c\right)}}{x-b}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(c-b\right)\left(c-a\right)}}{x-c}</me> 
      we have
      <me>\frac{1}{\left(x-z\right)\left(x-\bar{z}\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{\frac{1}{\left(z-\bar{z}\right)\left(z-c\right)}}{x-z}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(\bar{z}-z\right)\left(\bar{z}-c\right)}}{x-\bar{z}}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(c-\bar{z}\right)\left(c-z\right)}}{x-c}</me> 
    </p>


    <exercise>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that <m>\frac{1}{\left(c-\bar{z}\right)\left(c-z\right)}</m> is a real number.
        </p>

      </statement>
      
      <hint>
        <p>
          Note that <m>c-\bar{z}=\overline{c-z}</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>

    </exercise> 


    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>

        </p>
</introduction>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that 
      <me>
        \frac{\frac{1}{\left(z-\bar{z}\right)\left(z-c\right)}}{x-z}+\frac{\frac{1}{\left(\bar{z}-z\right)\left(\bar{z}-c\right)}}{x-\bar{z}}=\frac{-\frac{1}{\left(z-c\right)\left(\bar{z}-c\right)}x+\left(\frac{z}{\left(z-\bar{z}\right)\left(\bar{z}-c\right)}+\frac{\bar{z}}{\left(\bar{z}-z\right)\left(z-c\right)}\right)}{\left(x^2+ax+b\right)}
      </me> 
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      We already know that <m>-\frac{1}{\left(z-c\right)\left(\bar{z}-c\right)}</m> is a real number.  Show that 
      <me>\frac{z}{\left(z-\bar{z}\right)\left(\bar{z}-c\right)}+\frac{\bar{z}}{\left(\bar{z}-z\right)\left(z-c\right)}</me> 
      is a real number also.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      To avoid a lot of messy algebra, notice that these are conjugates.
    </p>
  </hint>

</task>

    </exercise>
              
    <p>
      Putting this all together, this says that 
      <me>
      \frac{1}{\left(x^2+ax+b\right)\left(x-c\right)}=\frac{Ax+B}{x^2+ax+b}+\frac{C}{x-c}
      </me> 
      where <m>A,B,C</m> are real numbers.  This is the PFD we were
      seeking.  This same idea will work for any denominator which is
      factored into linear or quadratic irreducible factors.
    </p>

            <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
</paragraphs>
  </subsection>






      <!-- <subsection > -->
      <!--   <title> This section needs to be cannibalized for example and -->
      <!--   exercises. Otherwise it should  go away.</title> -->



      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   As we<rsq/>ve mentioned before, all mathematical models are -->
      <!--   simplifications of reality, and typically are modified to -->
      <!--   take into account more complexities. For example, consider -->
      <!--   the following modification of the logistic model above -->
      <!--   <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)\left(\frac{y}{10}-1\right)=0.00001y(100-y)(y-10) -->
      <!--   </me> -->

      <!--   In this case, <m>10</m> is called the <term>minimum viability -->
      <!--   level</term> of the population. (Why?) Solving this would -->
      <!--   require that we compute the integral <me>\int -->
      <!--   \frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)(y-10)}</me>.  This form of this -->
      <!--   integral does not suggest any obvious trigonometric -->
      <!--   substitution so we will need a new idea. -->
      <!-- </p> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>partial fractions</h></idx> -->
      <!--   The next technique is wholly algebraic in nature. The trick -->
      <!--   to try and separate the integrand into <term>partial -->
      <!--   fractions</term> each of which will be easier to integrate -->
      <!--   than the original. For example, consider the expression -->
      <!--   <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}</m>. With begin by making a reasonable, -->
      <!--   educated guess that such a fraction can be written as -->
      <!--   <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}</m>, where -->
      <!--   <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are constant to be determined. We can -->
      <!--   see if this guess pans out by combining the partial fractions -->
      <!--   to obtain the original. -->
      <!--   <me>\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}=\frac{A(100-y)+By}{y(100-y)}=\frac{100A+(B-A)y}{y(100-y)}</me> -->
      <!--   Comparing this with <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}</m> we see that if -->
      <!--   they are to be equal we must have <m>100A=1</m> and -->
      <!--   <m>B-A=0</m>. Therefore <m>A=B=\frac{1}{100}</m>. Thus -->
      <!--   <me>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{1/100}{y}+\frac{1/100}{100-y}</me>. Substituting -->
      <!--   into the original integral we see that -->
      <!--   <md> -->
      <!--     <mrow> -->
      <!--       \int\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}\amp -->
      <!--     =\int\frac{1/100}{y}\dx{y}+\int\frac{1/100}{100-y}\dx{y}</mrow> -->
      <!--     <mrow>\amp -->
