      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   <term>The Partial Fraction Decomposition</term> -->
      <!--   <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>rational functions</h></idx> -->
      <!--   Now that we<rsq/>ve seen that decomposing a ratio of polynomials -->
      <!--   (these are called <term>rational functions</term>) into a sum -->
      <!--   of partial fractions is possible, we<rsq/>ll look for a systematic -->
      <!--   way of doing this for any <term> rational function -->
      <!--   </term>. Our method will hinge on the following theoretical, -->
      <!--   algebraic fact. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Suppose we have two polynomials <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> -->
      <!--   which have no common factors (other than constants). Then -->
      <!--   there are polynomials <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> such that -->
      <!--   <me>r(x)\cdot{}p(x)+s(x)\cdot{}q(x)=1</me>. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <example xml:id="ElementaryPartFracDecomp"> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     For example notice that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are -->
      <!--     constants then <m>x+a</m> and <m>x+b</m> have no common -->
      <!--     factors. Since <m>(x+a)-(x+b)=a-b</m> it follows that -->

      <!--     <me>\frac{1}{a-b}(x+a)+\frac{-1}{a-b}(x+b)=1</me>. -->

      <!--   </p> -->
      <!--   <aside> -->
      <!--     <title>Comment</title> -->
      <!--     <p> -->
      <!--       Notice that since <m>\frac{1}{a-b}</m> and -->
      <!--       <m>\frac{-1}{a-b}</m> are constants they are polynomials -->
      <!--       of degree zero. -->
      <!--     </p> -->
      <!--   </aside> -->
      <!-- </example> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Our approach to the problem in <xref -->
      <!--   ref="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">example</xref> was  somewhat -->
      <!--   ad<ndash/>hoc. We will eventualy need a more systematic approach but -->
      <!--   it will be useful to look at some more examples first. So for -->
      <!--   now we will use an       (educated) guess and check -->
      <!--   method. Notice that in the <xref -->
      <!--   ref="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">example</xref> we had -->
      <!--   <md> -->
      <!--     <mrow>\frac{1}{(x+a)(x+b)}\amp =\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}(x+a)+\frac{-1}{a-b}(x+b)}{(x+a)(x+b)}</mrow> -->
      <!--     <mrow>\amp = \frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+b}+\frac{\frac{-1}{a-b}}{x+a}</mrow> -->
      <!--     <mrow>\amp =\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+b}-\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+a} -->
      <!--     </mrow> -->
      <!--   </md> -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   It is generally true that if <m>r(x)\cdot p(x+s(x)\cdot -->
      <!--   q(x)=1</m> then -->
      <!--   <me>\frac{1}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=\frac{r(x)\cdot{}p(x)+s(x)\cdot{}q(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}= -->
      <!--   \frac{s(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{r(x)}{q(x)}</me>. Multiplying by -->
      <!--   <m>t(x)</m> we have <me>\frac{t(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}= -->
      <!--   \frac{t(x)\cdot -->
      <!--   s(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{t(x)\cdot{}r(x)}{q(x)}</me>.  Setting -->
      <!--   <m>A(x)=t(x)\cdot{}s(x)</m> and <m>B(x)=t(x)\cdot r(x)</m> -->
      <!--   gives -->
      <!--   <md> -->
      <!--     <mrow>\frac{t(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}= -->
      <!--     \frac{A(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{B(x)}{q(x)}</mrow> </md>. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Partial Fraction Decomposition</h></idx> -->
      <!--   Everything we<rsq/>ve just shown assumes that if <m>p(x)</m> and -->
      <!--   <m>q(x)</m> are known then <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> can be -->
      <!--   found so that <m>r(x)\cdot p(x)+ s(x)\cdot q(x)=1</m>. For -->
      <!--   arbitrary functions this is a very restrictive -->
      <!--   condition. However as we observed above, if <m>p(x)</m> and -->
      <!--   <m>q(x)</m> are polynomials having only trivial common -->
      <!--   factors then the existence of <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> is -->
      <!--   guaranteed. Thus for polynomials the <term> Partial Fraction -->
      <!--   Decomposition </term> is also guaranteed. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <aside> -->
      <!--   <title>Mathematical Terminology</title> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     The word <q>trivial</q> is very context dependent in -->
      <!--     mathematics. In this context a <q>trivial common factor</q> -->
      <!--     would be a constant. For example, <m>2</m> is a trivial -->
      <!--     common factor of <m>(2x-4)</m> and <m>2x+6</m>. -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!-- </aside> -->


      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   We formalize this in the following theorem. -->
      <!-- </p> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   As stated in <xref ref="PartialFractionDecomp">Theorem</xref> -->
      <!--   the PFD is very comprehensive. We will -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   To extend this idea further, if <m>p\left(x\right),\ -->
      <!--   q\left(x\right),\ r(x)</m> have no nontrivial factors, then -->
      <!--   there are polynomials <m>A\left(x\right),\ B\left(x\right),\ -->
      <!--   C(x)</m> with <me>\frac{t(x)}{p\left(x\right)\cdot -->
      <!--   q\left(x\right)\cdot -->
      <!--   r(x)}=\frac{A\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)}+\frac{B\left(x\right)}{q\left(x\right)}+\frac{C\left(x\right)}{r\left(x\right)}</me> -->
      <!--   and this can be extended to any number of factors in the -->
      <!--   denominator.  Again, this can be proven theoretically, and -->
      <!--   this partial fractions decomposition can be obtained -->
      <!--   systematically, but we will adopt a guess and check method to -->
      <!--   find <m>A,\ B,\ C</m>.  To make our guess a little more -->
      <!--   educated, the following fact can be employed.  You can make -->
      <!--   peace with this in your own closet. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   If the degree of <m>t(x)</m> is less than the degree of -->
