      <!-- </subsection> -->

      <exercises>
        <exercisegroup  cols="2">
          <title>Random Integrals</title>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Compute each of the integrals by any method you know.
              Some of these can be computed by more than one method.
            </p>

            <p>
              If you use complex numbers to compute the a PFD,
              recombine the appropriate root so that no complex
              numbers appear in your decomposition.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x^3}{2x-1}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{x^2+4}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x^2}{x^2+4}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x^3}{x^2+4}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x^2}{x^2-1}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{1-x^2}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{x^2+1}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x-3}{x^4-16}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x^3+5x}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{e^{2x}}{e^{2x}+1}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x+1}{x^3-x^2}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x^2+4}{(x^2+1)^2(x^2+2)}\dx{x}</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>


        </exercisegroup>
      </exercises>
    </section>

<section  xml:id="SECTIONIntParts">
  <title>Running the Product Rule Backwards: Integration By Parts  </title>
  <example xml:id="EXAMPLENonHomDiffeq">
    <title>Population Dynamics: A Non<ndash/>Separable Differential Equation</title>

    <p>
      Recall that in <xref ref="EXAMPLEExpGrowthSepDiffeq"></xref>
      we solved the differential equation <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=Ky </m> by
      separating the variables and then integrating. This is the
      equation we used to model the exponential growth of an algal
      bloom which we first saw in <xref
      ref="SECTIONExponentialGrowth"></xref>.
      For reasons that will become clear shortly we re<ndash/>write
      will this equation as <men
      xml:id="EQUATIONPopPerturb1">\dfdx{y}{t}-Ky =0</men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <xref ref="EQUATIONPopPerturb1">Equation</xref> assumes that
      the relative growth rate, <m>K</m> in this case, is
      constant. But that is almost never true.  All biological
      processes including reproduction tend to slow down when the
      ambient temperature is cooler and to speed up when it is
      warmer. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Suppose for example, that we have a population of algae
      growing in a pond. At night when the temperature is cooler
      the rate of growth will slow and during the daytime it will
      speed up. For simplicity of demonstration we<rsq/>ll suppose
      that the <q>speeding up and slowing down</q> takes the form
      of a cosine wave, <m>\cos(t) </m>.  This means that the rate
      of change of our algae population will be
      <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=Ky+\cos (t)</m> because the rate of growth of
      our population is still proportional to the size of the
      population. To be consistent with <xref
      ref="EQUATIONPopPerturb1">equation</xref> we<rsq/>ll
      re<ndash/>write this as <me>\dfdx{y}{t}-Ky=\cos (t)</me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      To complete our model we<rsq/>ll assume that initally
      there are <m>20</m> kilograms of algae in the pond. Thus
      to find the population as a function of time we need to
      solve the IVP
      <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">\dfdx{y}{t} - Ky \amp{}=\cos(t),\amp{} y(0)=20.</mrow>
      </mdn>
    </p>
    <p>
      The differential equation part of <xref
      ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> is not separable but it is
      very similar to <men
      xml:id="EQUATIONExpGrowthHom">\dfdx{y}{t}-Ky=0 </men> whose
      solution <men xml:id="EQUATIONPopDynHomSol">y(t)=Ae^{Kt}</men>
      is known.  Since the equations are similar it seems reasonable
      to suppose that their solutions will also be similar so the
      question is, <q>How do we tweak <xref
      ref="EQUATIONPopDynHomSol">solution</xref>) so as to obtain a
      solution of <xref ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref>?</q>
    </p>
    <p>
      Observe that <m>y(t)=Ae^{Kt}</m> is the product of the
      constant <m>A</m> and the function <m>e^{Kt}</m>, One
      possible tweak is to suppose that the solution of <xref
      ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> is also a product. But
      since this is a slightly more complex problem than <xref
      ref="EQUATIONPopDynRedux">equation</xref> we need a slightly
      more complex product. So let<rsq/>s guess that 
      <me>\bar{y}(t)=A(t)\cdot e^{Kt}</me>
      where <m>A(t)</m> is a differentiable function rather than
      a constant.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        We have called this a guess because ultimately, that<rsq/>s
        all it really is. As such it is simply a trick. But we have
        also said that a <q>technique</q> is a <q>trick</q> that is
        used more than once.
      </p>
      <p>
        The way we found <m>A(t)</m>   is the 
        technique called <q>Variation of Parameters</q> and it works
        like this. The
        solution of <xref ref="EQUATIONPopPerturb1">equation</xref> contains
        the parameter <m>A</m> which is a constant. To solve <xref
        ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> we <q>vary</q> the
        parameter <m>A</m> by pretending that it is a function
        rather than a constant. Then we proceed to find out what
        function <m>A(t)</m> has to be.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      Having made our guess the only thing to do now is try it in
      <xref ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> and see if it
      works.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is we suppose that <m>\bar{y}(t) = A(t)\cdot e^{Kt}</m>
      is a solution of <xref ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> and
      try to find out what <m>A(t)</m> must be. From the Product
      Rule we see that
      <me>\dfdx{\bar{y}}{t}=A(t)Ke^{Kt}+\dfdx{A}{t}e^{Kt}</me>. Putting
      this into our differential equation in <xref
      ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> we have 
      <md>
        <mrow>\underbrace{\textcolor{red}{AKe^{Kt}}+\dfdx{A}{t}e^{Kt}}_{=\dfdx{\bar{y}}{t}}-\underbrace{\textcolor{red}{KA(t)e^{Kt}}}_{=K\bar{y}}\amp{}=\cos(t)</mrow>
        <mrow>
          \dfdx{A}{t}e^{Kt}\amp{}=\cos{t}.
        </mrow>
      </md>
      So apparently all we have left to do is compute the
      integral <men xml:id="EQUATIONVarParamSimple">A(t) = \int
      e^{-Kt}\cos (t)\dx{t}</men> to find <m>A(t)</m> and the
      solution of <xref ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom"></xref> will be
      <me>\bar{y}=A(t)e^{Kt}</me>.

    </p>


    <p>
      Unfortunately this is
      well beyond our ability at the moment so we will back up a
      bit and look at some slightly simpler integrals first.
    </p>

    <!--   This is why we re<ndash/>wrote our differential equations the way we -->
    <!--   did. On the left side of both we have  -->
    <!--   <me>\dfdx{y}{t}-Ky</me>. If you look closely at that expression you -->
    <!--   can  almost see -->
    <!--   the result of a <xref ref="THEOREMProdRule" text="custom">Product -->
    <!--   Rule</xref> which suggests that that our solution -->
    <!--   <mdash/>let<rsq/>s call it <m>\bar{y}(t)</m> <mdash/> is -->
    <!--   probably a product of two functions. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Look at <xref ref="EQUATIONPopDynHomSol">equation </xref> -->
    <!--   again.  -->
    <!-- </p> -->

    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Of course we can<rsq/>t just multiply one side of an equation by -->
    <!--   something just because we like the outcome, so we<rsq/>ll multiply -->
    <!--   both sides of <xref ref="EQUATIONExpGrowthHom">equation</xref> -->
    <!--   instead, giving -->
    <!--   <me>\underbrace{e^{-Kt}\dfdx{y}{t}-e^{-Kt}Ky}_{=\dfdx{\left(e^{-Kt}\cdot -->
    <!--   y\right)}{t}}=0\cdot e^{-Kt}</me> -->
    <!--   or -->
    <!--   <me>\dfdx{\left(e^{-Kt}\cdot  y\right)}{t}=0</me>. -->
    <!--   From there we can recover the solution of <xref -->
    <!--   ref="EQUATIONExpGrowthHom"></xref> by integrating -->
    <!--   <md> -->
    <!--     <mrow>\int\dfdx{\left(e^{-Kt}\cdot  y\right)} {t}\dx{t}\amp{}=\int0\dx{t}</mrow> -->
    <!--     <mrow> -->
    <!--       e^{-Kt}\cdot  y \amp{}= A -->
    <!--     </mrow> -->
    <!--     <mrow> -->
    <!--       y(t)\amp{}=Ae^{Kt}. -->
    <!--     </mrow> -->
    <!--   </md>  -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   If we apply the same technique to      <xref -->
    <!--   ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> we  get -->
    <!--   <me> -->
    <!--     \int\dfdx{\left(e^{-Kt}\cdot  y\right)} -->
    <!--     {t}\dx{t}=e^{-Kt}\cdot y =\int -->
    <!--     e^{-Kt}\cos(t)\dx{t} -->
    <!--     </me>. -->
    <!--     Clearly to solve this problem we will need to be able to -->
    <!--     compute <m>\int e^t\cos(t) \dx{t}</m>.  -->

  </example>

  <p>
    Consider the integral <men xml:id="EQUATIONPartsXCos"> \int x\cos(x)\dx{x} </men>.
    Try as you might you will find that no substitution you can find
    will work here. Nor will the Partial Fraction Decomposition  help.
  </p>
  <aside> 
    <title>Comment</title>
    <p>
      Actually, we should be more careful.  There is <em> always
      </em> a substitution that will work. For example, the
      substitution 
      <me>u=x\sin(x) +\cos (x)</me> will work here.
    </p>
    <p>
      The question is, can we find
      it? How do you think we found this one?
    </p>
  </aside>
  <paragraphs>
    <title>DIGRESSION: How Not  to Integrate a Product</title>
    <p>
      In the beginning a common error is to assume that that we need
      only integrate the two factors separately. If we do that with <xref ref="EQUATIONPartsXCos">formula</xref> 
      we<rsq/>ll get <me>\frac{x^2}{2}\sin(x) +C</me>.  This is not
      correct as we can easily verify by differentiation.  Moreover,
      we know that the differential of a product is not the product
      of the differentials, so on second thought that may seem like
      it was a silly idea. It was not. It is the most natural
      assumption we can make. But it is an assumption, not
      knowledge, and when it is examined closely it comes up short
      as we have just seen.
    </p>
    <p>
      So we need a new idea. 
    </p>
    <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
  </paragraphs>

  <p>
    In <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>
    we listed the integration rules corresponding to the <xref
    ref="THEOREMConstRule" text="custom">Constant Rule</xref> (#1), the <xref
    ref="THEOREMSumRule" text="custom">Sum Rule</xref> (#2), the <xref
    ref="THEOREMConstMultRule" text="custom">Constant Multiple Rule</xref> (#3),
    and <xref ref="THEOREMGenPowRule" text="custom">Power Rule</xref> (#4), but
    not 
    the <xref ref="THEOREMProdRule" text="custom">Product Rule</xref>?
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Comment</title>
    <p>
      We didn<rsq/>t give an integration rule corresponding to the
      <xref ref="THEOREMQuotientRule" text="custom">Quotient Rule</xref>
      either. But we don<rsq/>t need that one since the Quotient
      Rule can be thought of as a rearrangement of the Product Rule.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <p>
    It is time to fill in that blank so we will try to <q>run the
    Power Rule backward,</q> if we can.
    <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Integration by Parts</h></idx> In
    differential form Product Rule formula is
    <me>\dx(uv)=v\dx{u}+u\dx{v}</me>.  To run this backwards we
    integrate both sides giving <me>\int \dx(uv)=\int v\dx{u}+\int
    u\dx{v}</me>, which is equivalent to

    <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntPartsForm">\int u\dx{v}=\int
    \dx(uv)-\int v\dx{u}
    </men>.
    Observing that
    <m>\int \dx(uv)=uv</m>, yields the
    Integration by Parts formula (in differential form):
    <me>              \int{}u\dx{v} =uv-\int{}v\dx{u}</me>.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Comment</title>
    <p>
      Strictly speaking <m>\int \dx(uv)=uv</m> plus an arbitrary
      constant. We are ignoring the constant for reasons that will
      be clear soon.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   OK, but what are <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> and how can we use  the -->
  <!--   Integration by Parts formula to integrate something like -->
  <!--   <m>\int x\cos(x) \dx{x}</m>?  -->
  <!--   <!-\- As useful as Leibniz<rsq/>s differential notation has been for -\-> -->
  <!--   <!-\- us here is a place where it is less clear than the prime -\-> -->
  <!--   <!-\- notation of Lagrange. -\-> -->
  <!--   Let  -->
  <!--   <md> -->
  <!--     <mrow>f(t)=u(t)\amp{}\amp{}\text{ and }\amp{}\amp{} -->
  <!--     g(t)=v(t)   \amp{}\amp{} -->
  <!--     </mrow> -->
  <!--     <intertext> -->
  <!--       so -->
  <!--       that  -->
  <!--     </intertext> -->
  <!--     <mrow> -->
  <!--       \dx{u}=f^\prime(t)\dx{t}\amp{}\amp{} \text{ and }\amp{}\amp{} -->
  <!--       \dx{v}=g^\prime(t)\dx{t}      -->
  <!--     </mrow> -->
  <!--   </md> -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   Making these substitutions into <xref -->
  <!--   ref="EQUATIONIntPartsForm">equation</xref> we get the -->
  <!--   Integration by Parts formula in its functional form -->
  <!--   <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntPartsLagrange">  -->
  <!--     \int{}f(x)g^\prime(x)\dx{x} = -->
  <!--     f(x)\cdot g(x)-\int -->
  <!--     g(x)f^\prime(x) \dx{x} -->
  <!--   </men> -->
  <!--   . -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIntxcosx">
    <p>
      To integrate <m>\int x\cos (x)\dx{x}</m>  by parts we set 
      <md>
        <mrow>
          u=x\amp{}\amp{}\text{ and } \amp{}\amp{}
          \dx{v}=\cos(x)\dx{x}
        </mrow>
        <intertext>
          so that
        </intertext>
        <mrow>
          \dx{u}=\dx{x} \amp{}\amp{}\text{ and } \amp{}\amp{}
          v=\int\cos(x)\dx{x} = \sin(x).
        </mrow>
      </md>
      Making these substitutions gives        
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \int x\cos(x)\dx{x} = \int u\dx{v}\amp{}=uv-\int v\dx{u}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=x\sin(x) -\int \sin (x)\dx{x}.
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp{}=x\sin(x) + \cos (x).
        </mrow> 
      </md>
      and, finally
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntxCosx"> 
        \int x\cos(x)\dx{x} = x\sin(x) + \cos (x) +C
      </men>
    </p>

  </example>

  <p>
    It is worth taking a moment to notice a few facts about
    Integration by Parts.
    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>Integration by Parts is Not a Substitution.</title>
        <p>
          After <m>u</m> and <m>\dx{v}</m> are chosen we do not get
          an integral in terms of <m>u</m> and  <m>v</m> which we then need to transform back into an integral
          in terms of <m>x</m>, the way we did with Integration by
          Substitution.  The variables <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> were
          introduced just to keep track of the Integration by
          Parts formula. The resulting integral will be in terms
          of the original variable.
        </p>

      </li>

      <li>
        <title>In Choosing <m>u</m> and <m>\dx{v}</m> We Used Up  the Entire
        Integrand and the Differential.</title>
        <p>
          That is, in <xref ref="EXAMPLEIntxcosx"></xref> the
          expression <m>u\dx{v}</m> is exactly equal to 
          <m>x\cos(x)\dx{x}</m>. Nothing was left out except the
          integral sign, <m>\int{}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          As a practical matter this means that once you have
          decided what to call <m>u</m> then <m>\dx{v}</m> is
          everything else to the right of the <m>\int </m> symbol. 
        </p>
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   Also notice that <m>\dx{x}</m> is always part of -->
        <!--   <m>\dx{v}</m>. -->
        <!-- </p> -->


      </li>

      <li>
        <title>Integration By Parts Does Not Compute the
        Integral.</title>
        <p>
          Rather, it replaces that integral with another,
          hopefully one that is easier to compute.
          (This is actually true of all of the integration
          techniques. They do not compute the integral, they
          just seek to replace it with an integral that we
          already know.)
        </p>
        <p>
          In <xref
          ref="EXAMPLEIntxcosx"></xref>, for instance, we could
          have let <m>u=\cos(x){}</m> and
          <m>\dx{u}=x\dx{x}</m>. This would give
          <m>v=x^2/2</m>. Substituting these into <m>\int x\cos(x)
          \dx{x}</m> we get
          <me>
            \int x\cos(x)\dx{x}=\frac{x^2}{2}\cos(x)+\frac{1}{2}\int
            x^2\sin(x)\dx{x}
            </me>.
            
            Everything we<rsq/>ve done is valid, but the integral
            on the right is actually harder to evaluate than the
            one we started with.
        </p>
        <p>
          What this means in practice is that as long as the integration by
          parts technique is applied correctly, it is not
          wrong in any absolute sense. But it might not be very
          helpful in computing the integral in front of us. So if your
          first attempt to compute an integral doesn<rsq/>t seem
          to be going anywhere step back and ask yourself if
          another choice of <m>u</m> and <m>\dx{v}</m>, or even
          a different integration technique might work better.
        </p>



      </li>
    </dl>
  </p>


  <problem>
    <p>
      Show that <m> \int x\cos(x)\dx{x} = x\sin(x) + \cos (x)
      +C</m> by differentiating the right side.
    </p>
  </problem>

  <p>
    The following  <xref ref="THEOREMIntegrationByParts" text="custom">theorem</xref> is the formal
    statement of Integration by Parts, in both differential and
    functional (modern) form.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMIntegrationByParts">
    <title>Integration by Parts</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Differential Form:</alert>
            <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntPartsDiff">
              \int{}u\dx{v} =uv-\int{}v\dx{u}
            </men>
            .
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Functional Form:</alert>
            <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntPartsFunc"> 
              \int{}f(x)g^\prime(x)\dx{x} =
              f(x)\cdot g(x)-\int
              g(x)f^\prime(x) \dx{x}
            </men>
            .
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    Finding a choice for <m>u</m> and <m>\dx{v} </m> that will work
    is mostly a matter of using your intuition. But unfortunately,
    at first you have no such intuition. There is nothing to be done
    but take a stab at it. Make a choice and then do the
    computations that follow from it. At first your choices
    won<rsq/>t work and this can be frustrating. But learn from your
    efforts. Try again. And keep trying. With practice intuition
    will develop. In time you might even find that you enjoy the
    process. Really. Many students do.
  </p>

  <p>
    In any case, practice is necessary. Lots of practice.
  </p>

  <problem>
    <p>
      Use Integration by Parts to compute each integral, then verify
      that your solution is correct by differentiation.

      <ol cols="2" marker="(i)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\sin(x)\dx{x}
            </m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\cos(x/2) \dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{3}\sin (5x)\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int xe^{\frac{x}{2}}\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\cosh(x) \dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\sinh(x) \dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\inverse \tan (x)\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\inverse \sin (x)\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x\ln (x)\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int x^2\ln (x)\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li> 
      </ol>
    </p>
  </problem>



  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Did you notice that in <xref
        ref="EXAMPLEIntxcosx"></xref> we suppressed the arbitrary
        constant when we computed <m>v</m>? This is because once we
        have chosen <m>\dx{v}</m>, any antiderivative will
        work as  this problem shows.
      </p>
    </introduction>        
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral <m>\int
          x\cos(x)\dx{x}</m> letting <m>u=x</m> again, letting
          <m>\dx{v}=\cos(x)\dx{x}</m> as before. But this
          time  take <m>y=\sin(x)+a</m> where <m>a</m> is an
          arbitrary constant. Show that we will obtain the same
          answer as before.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that in general, if we let <m>\int\dx{v}=v+a</m> in
          the integration by parts formula, then we still obtain
          the formula <me>\int u\dx{v}=uv-\int v\dx{u}.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          You may find it helpful to use the functional form of
          Integration by Parts in <xref ref="THEOREMIntegrationByParts"></xref>.
        </p>
      </hint>

    </task>
    
    <conclusion>
      <p>
        Since keeping  track of the arbitrary constant in subsequent
        computations complicates thing for no purpose it is usually
        ignored. But don<rsq/>t forget to tack on the
        <q><m>+C</m></q> at the end of an Integration by Parts.
      </p>
    </conclusion>

  </exercise>



  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Integration by Parts</h></idx>       -->
  <!--   As we<rsq/>ve indicated when it is written in this  form the Product -->
  <!--   Rule  is called  -->
  <!--   <term>Integration by Parts</term> and it is -->
  <!--   exactly what we need to compute the previous integral. -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIntParts1"> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     Specifically, if we let <m>u=x</m> and -->
  <!--     <m>\dx{v}=\cos(x)\dx{x}</m>, then <m>\dx{u}=\dx{x}</m> and -->
  <!--     <m>v=\int\cos(x)\dx{x}=\sin(x) </m> (don<rsq/>t worry about the -->
  <!--     arbitrary constant here for the moment. We<rsq/>ll look at it later.). -->
  <!--     Substituting these into our integration by parts formula, -->
  <!--     <men xml:id="IntByParts"> -->
  <!--       \int{}u\dx{v} =uv-\int v\dx{u} -->
  <!--     </men> -->
  <!--     we have -->
  <!--     <me> -->
  <!--       \int x\cos(x)\dx{x} = -->
  <!--       x\sin(x)-\int\sin(x)\dx{x}=x\sin(x){}+\cos(x)+c  -->
  <!--       </me>. -->
  <!--     </p> -->

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMIntInvFunc">
    <title>Integrals of Inverse Functions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        So far we  have found, by various means, the integrals of the
        sine, cosine, tangent, cotangent, secant, cosecant, and natural
        exponential functions.
        We have held off on finding the antiderivative of the inverses
        of those functions because that is most easily done using
        Integration by Parts.

      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use Integration by Parts to compute each of the
          integrals. Confirm your results by differentiation.
          <ol cols="3" marker="(i)">
            <li>
              <m>\int \inverse \sin (x)\dx{x}</m>

            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \inverse \cos (x)\dx{x}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \inverse \tan (x)\dx{x}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \inverse \cot (x)\dx{x}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \inverse \sec (x)\dx{x}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \inverse \csc (x)\dx{x}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int  \ln (x)\dx{x}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>

        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          There are really only two choices for <m>u</m>. If your  first choice
          doesn<rsq/>t work try the other one.
        </p>
      </hint>

    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>F(x)=\int xf^\prime(x)\dx{x}</m>.
          Generalize the results in part (a) by showing that
          <me>\int \inverse{f}(x)\dx{x}= xf(x)-F(x)</me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>


  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercise> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </exercise> -->

  <!-- <aside> -->
  <!--   <title>A Word of Advice</title> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     Rather than trying to memorize this integral, just remember -->
  <!--     to use integration by parts. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </aside> -->


  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   As with differentiation techniques and formulas, techniques -->
  <!--   such as integration by parts and substitution are performed in -->
  <!--   concert, utilizing whatever technique that is appropriate at -->
  <!--   the time.  As an example of this consider the next problem. -->
  <!-- </p> -->

  <!-- <exercise> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     Perform integration by parts and then substitution to -->
  <!--     compute <m>\int \inverse\sin(x)\dx{x}</m> and <m>\int -->
  <!--     \inverse\tan(x)\dx{x}</m>. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </exercise> -->
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   Just as integration by parts can be used with other -->
  <!--   techniques, it can be used with itself multiple times. -->
  <!-- </p> -->
  <!-- <aside> -->
  <!--   <title>A Word of Advice</title> -->
  <!--   <p> -->
  <!--     If you perform integration by parts twice, be sure not to -->
  <!--     switch the roles of <q><m>u</m></q> and <q><m>v</m>.</q> This -->
  <!--     is not incorrect, but the second integration will simply undo -->
  <!--     the first integration and circle back to where you -->
  <!--     started. Try it and see. -->
  <!--   </p> -->
  <!-- </aside> -->

  <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEIntPartsMultiple">

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p> 
          Use Integration by Parts to show that 
          <me> \int x^2e^x\dx{x} = x^2e^x-2\int xe^x\dx{x}</me>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Notice that the formula in part (a) does not complete the
          integration. Explain what else we need to do to find the
          antiderivative of <m>x^2e^x</m> and then do that. Confirm 
          your result by differentiation.
        </p>
      </statement>

    </task>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    As with differentiation it is rare that a single integration
    technique is sufficient to compute a given antiderivative. Usually
    two or more diffent techniques are required because as we<rsq/>ve
    seen none of the methods actually compute the integral. They simply
    replace it with another. If we don<rsq/>t know the new integral,
    from memory or from <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>, we
    will have to integrate again using whatever technique is appropriate
    to the new problem.
  </p>


  <problem>
    <p>
      As we saw in <xref ref="EXERCISEIntPartsMultiple"></xref> sometimes
      we have to use the same integration technique more than once.  If
      you perform integration by parts twice, be sure not to switch the
      roles of <q><m>u</m></q> and <q><m>v</m>.</q> This is not incorrect,
      but the second integration will simply undo the first integration
      and circle back to where you started. Try it and see.
    </p>

    <p>
      To see what we mean
      integrate <m>\int x^2\sin(x) \dx{x}</m> by parts twice. The first
      time let <m>u=x^2</m> and <m>\dx{v}=\sin(x)\dx{x}</m>  and the
      second time let <m>u=\cos(x)</m> and <m>\dx{v}=x\dx{x}</m> to
      confirm that the second Integration by Parts simply undoes the
      first. 
    </p>
  </problem>


  <exercise>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider 
          <me> 
            \int e^x\sin(x)\dx{x}
            </me>. 
            Use Integration by Parts to show that 
            <!-- If we let -->
            <!-- <m>u=e^x</m> and <m>\dx{v} =\sin(x)\dx{x}</m>, then -->
            
            <!-- <md> -->
            <!--   <mrow>u\amp{}=e^x \amp{}\dx{v}\amp{}=\sin(x)\dx{x}</mrow> -->
            <!--   <mrow>\dx{u}\amp{}=e^x\dx{x}\amp{} v\amp{}=-\cos(x)\dx{x}</mrow> -->
            <!-- </md> -->
            <!-- so -->
            <me>
              \int e^x\sin(x)\dx{x} = -e^x\cos(x){}+\int e^x\cos(x)\dx{x}.
            </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Apply integration by parts again (being careful not
          to switch the roles of <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>) to show that 

          <!-- <md> -->
          <!--   <mrow>u\amp{}=e^x \amp{} \dx{v}\amp{}=\cos(x)\dx{x}</mrow> -->
          <!--   <mrow>\dx{u}\amp{}=e^x\dx{x}\amp{} \sin(x){}</mrow> -->
          <!-- </md> -->
          <!-- so -->
          <me>
            \int e^x\sin(x)\dx{x}=<!-- -e^x\cos(x)+\left[e^x\sin(x)-\int -->
            <!-- e^x\sin(x)\dx{x}\right]{}= -->-e^x\cos(x)+e^x\sin(x)-\int
            e^x\sin(x)\dx{x}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          It looks like we went full circle in part (b) and came back to
          where we started. But look again.
          <!--   If we let <m>I=\int -->
          <!-- e^x\sin(x)\dx{x}</m>, we see that this is now a simple -->
          <!-- algebra problem since -->
          <!-- <me> -->
          <!--   I=-e^x\cos(x){+e^x\sin(x){-I}} -->
          <!-- </me> -->
          Explain how we can conclude from the result in part (b) that 
          <me>
            \int e^x\sin(x)\dx{x}= \frac{e^x}{2}(\sin(x)-\cos(x))+C
            </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <conclusion>
      <p>
        Notice that we had to remember to add the arbitrary constant
        since there is no point in the calculation where it appears
        naturally .
      </p>
    </conclusion>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMNonHomDiffeq">
    <title><xref ref="EXAMPLENonHomDiffeq"></xref>, Solved</title>
    <introduction>

      <p>
        We are finally in a position to complete <xref
        ref="EXAMPLENonHomDiffeq"></xref>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Integrate the right<ndash/>hand
          side of <xref ref="EQUATIONVarParamSimple">equation</xref> to
          show that 
          <me>A(t) = \frac{1}{1+K^2}\left[\sin(t)-K\cos(t)\right]+C
          </me>
          Where <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the solution of <xref
          ref="IVPExpGrowthNonHom">IVP</xref> is 
          <me>\bar{y}=\frac{1}{1+K^2}\left[ \sin(t) -K\cos (t)\right] + Ce^{Kt}</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the initial condition <m>\bar{y}(0)=20</m> to determine
          <m>C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>



  </exercise>


  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Compute each integral. Confirm your result by differentiation.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>          \displaystyle\int x\cos(x) \dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>       \displaystyle\int x^2\sin(x)\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>    \displaystyle\int \sqrt{x}\cos( \sqrt{x} )\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m> \displaystyle\int x^{\frac32}\sin( \sqrt{x} )\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m> \displaystyle\int\frac{xe^x}{(2+2x)^2}\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle\int x^3e^{5x}\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>        \displaystyle\int (\ln(x))^2 \dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>        \int (\ln(x))^3 \dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>n</m> is a positive integer. We want to compute the integral
        <me>\int \sin^n(x) \dx{x}</me>. 
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          First 
          let <m>u=\sin^{n-1}</m> and <m>\dx{v}=\sin (x)\dx{x}</m> and show
          that 
          <me>\int \sin^n (x)\dx{x} =
          -\frac1n \cos(x) \sin^{n-1} (x)+(n-1)\int \sin^{n-2}(x)\cos^2(x)
          \dx{x}</me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show
          that 
          <me>\int \sin^n (x)\dx{x} =
          -\frac1n \cos(x) \sin^{n-1} (x)+(n-1)\int \sin^{n-2}(x)
          \dx{x}-(n-1)\int \sin^n(x) \dx{x}</me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Observe that <m>\cos^2(x) =1-\sin^2(x) </m>.
        </p>
      </hint>

    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain how the result in part (b) implies that 
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONSineReduction1">
            \int \sin^n (x)\dx{x} =
            -\frac1n \cos(x) \sin^{n-1} (x)+ \frac{n-1}{n}\int \sin^{n-2}(x)
            \dx{x}
            </men>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>


  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMIntProdProdInt">
    <title>When the Integral of a Product is the Product of the
    Integrals</title>
    

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>f^\prime(x)\neq{}f(x)</m> Show that if <me>
          \left(f\cdot g\right)^\prime(x) = f^\prime(x)\cdot
          g^\prime(x) </me> then
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONProdDerivs">
            g(x)=\exp\left({\int{\frac{1}{1-\frac{f(x)}{f^\prime(x)}}}\dx{x}{}}\right)
          </men>
        </p>
        <p>
          (Don<rsq/>t let this <xref ref="EQUATIONProdDerivs">formula</xref>
          frighten you. Recall that <m>\exp(x)=e^x</m>.)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Apply <xref ref="EQUATIONProdDerivs">equation</xref> to the
          function <m>f(x)=x^n</m> and compare this to the results in
          Problem # 60 above.  <me> \int{}u\dx{v}{}=\int{}
          \left(\dx(uv) -v\dx{u}{}\right) = \int\dx(uv) -\int
          v\dx{u}{=uv-\int v\dx{u} }.</me> or <men
          xml:id="EQUATIONIntegrationByParts">\int{}u\dx{v}{}=uv-\int
          v\dx{u}</men>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>
</section>

<section xml:id="SECTIONStoneArch">
  <title>  Bridge Arches, the Catenary Curve, and Integration</title>
  <p>
    In <xref ref="SUBSECTIONDomes"></xref> we mentioned that when <url
    href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Wren/"
    visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Wren/">Sir
    Christopher Wren</url>(1632<ndash/>1723) designed the dome of
    <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Paul%27s_Cathedral"
         visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Paul%27s_Cathedral">St
    Paul<rsq/>s Cathedral</url> he was advised by his friend <url
    href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Hooke/"
    visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Hooke/">Robert
    Hooke</url> (1635<ndash/>1703) as follows:
  </p>
  <blockquote>

    <p>

      As hangs a flexible cable so, inverted, stand the touching pieces
      of an arch.

    </p>
  </blockquote>
  <p>
    Hooke is advising Wren that for maximum stability he should design the dome of
    St. Christopher<rsq/>s so that every cross section through the
    center of the dome would be  a catenary curve:
    <me>
      y=\frac{1}{a}\cosh(ax)=\frac{1}{2a}\left(e^{ax}+e^{-ax}\right)
    </me>
    where <m>a</m> is an appropriate constant.
  </p>
  <p>
    We<rsq/>ve also mentioned that masons had concluded from centuries
    of experience based on trial and error that the best shape for a
    stone bridge is an inverted catenary .
  </p>


  <figure  xml:id="FIGUREStoneArch">
    <caption>
    </caption>
    <image source="IC/DianasPool.png" width="70%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>
  <!-- <p> -->
  <!--   Utilizing calculus -->
  <!--   in our analysis of the problem, we finally determined why the -->
  <!--   most stable freestanding arch utilizes this shape.  This shape -->
  <!--   is the one which directs the weight of the chain tangentially -->
  <!--   toward the base of the arch.  It turns out that the same sort of -->
  <!--   analysis can be used to determine the <q>best</q> shape for the -->
  <!--   arch on a stone bridge. -->
  <!-- </p> -->


  <p>
    <!-- To make the most stable arch for such a bridge, we wish to direct -->
    <!-- the weight of the bridge tangentially toward the base as well. -->
    <!-- Our mathematical analysis is below.   -->
    To see why this is so consider one half of a stone arch bridge as
    represented in the schematic below.  We will draw the positive
    <m>y</m>-axis downward and focus on the forces at a generic point
    <m>P</m> with coordinates <m>(x,y)</m>. Our analysis will be very
    similar to our analysis of the suspension bridge cable in <xref
    ref="SUBSECTIONBridges"></xref>.
  </p>

  <image source="IC/StoneArch6.png" width="75%">
    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
  </image>
  <!-- <image source="IC/StoneArch1.png" width="70%"> -->
  <!--   <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
  <!-- </image> -->

  <p>
    The problem is to find the curve <m>y=y(x)</m> with the property
    that the 
    vertical component of the tangential force <m>T</m>, at <m>P</m>, is
    equal to the weight of the bridge from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m>.  
    <!-- If -->
    <!-- we do this, then that means that the weight of the bridge will be -->
    <!-- directed toward the base of the bridge.  With this in mind,
    -->
    Let <m>A(x)</m> denote the cross<ndash/>sectional area of the
    bridge from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m>. There are two facts about
    <m>A(x)</m> that we will need:
    <ol marker="(1)">
      <li>
        <p>
          The weight of bridge from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m> is
          proportional to <m>A(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>A(x)=\int\dx{A}</m>.
        </p>

      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <p>
    Next we denote by <m>H</m>  the
    (constant) magnitude of the horizontal force along the length of
    the bridge and by <m>w</m> be the weight density of the stone (per
    cross sectional area) so that the weight of the bridge from
    <m>0</m> to <m>x</m> is <m>wA</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Recall that we want  the horizontal
    component of the force <m>T</m> to be <m>H</m> and the vertical
    component to be the weight of the bridge from <m>0</m> to
    <m>x</m>, namely, <m>wA</m>.  This leads to the following picture,



    from which we conclude that the slope of the tangent line to
    <m>y(x)</m> at <m>(x,y)</m> is equal to <m>\frac{w}{H}</m>.
  </p>
  <image source="IC/StoneArch9.png" width="75%">
    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
  </image>
  <p>
    And so we have the differential equation
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONArch1"> \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{w}{H}A</men>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem here is that we don<rsq/>t know what <m>A</m> is.
    However, we do know what <m>dA</m> is. Do you see it?
  </p>
  <p>
    We will return to that in a moment, but first 
    differentiating <xref ref="EQUATIONArch1">equation</xref>  we see that  the arch
    should satisfy the differential equation
    <men  xml:id="EQUATIONArch2">\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H}\dfdx{A}{x}</men>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Returning to <m>\dx{A}</m>  we form the
    infinitesimal rectangle whose base is <m>\dx{x}</m> and whose
    height is <m>y</m> as  in the sketch below.
  </p>
  <image source="IC/StoneArch8.png" width="75%">
    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
  </image>

  <p>
    Notice that the area of that rectangle is a differential since
    it is the product of the real number <m>y</m> and the
    differential <m>\dx{x}</m>. Moreover the sum of the areas of all
    such rectangles is clearly <m>A</m> so it must be that
    <me>\dx{A}=y\dx{x}</me>.  Substituting this into <xref
    ref="EQUATIONArch2">equation</xref> we find that
    <me>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H}\dfdx{A}{x}=\frac{w}{H} y</me>.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMStoneArch">
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that
          <me>y=Ae^{\sqrt{\frac{w}{H}}x}+Be^{-\sqrt{\frac{w}{H}}x}</me>
          satisfies the above differential equation for any constants <m>A,\ B</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that if <m>y\left(0\right)=\sqrt{\frac{H}{w}}</m> and
          <m>{\left.\dfdx{y}{x}\right|}_{x=0}=0</m>, then
          <m>A=B=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\frac{H}{w}}</m>.  Compare this to the
          equation of the catenary in <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain"></xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    While it is interesting that the above example illustrates the
    importance of catenaries in engineering, the important thing for
    us is that since <m>\dx{A}=y\dx{x}</m> we see that
    <me>\int{y\dx{x}=\int\dx{A}=A+c}</me> which relates integrals to
    areas.  This relationship was known to both Newton and Leibniz,
    as well as some of their predecessors.  It is of such importance
    that it has come to be known by the, somewhat bombastic, name
    <term>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</term>.  We will
    explore this idea more carefully in the next section and develop
    a more precise notation to deal with the applications of
    integration.
  </p>

</section>
</chapter>

